One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, in the US, individual states are responsible for organising federal elections.
And in this spirit, most U.S. governments have been promulgating new laws since 2009 that make the process of voting or registering on the electoral roll more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 election, during which 675 new Republican representatives were added in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the franchise in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws restrict the early voting period, invalidate the right to register on the electoral roll on election day, and deprive citizens with a criminal record of voting rights.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present photo ID.
The first state to introduce this requirement was Indiana.
The constitutionality of the Indian law was upheld by the U.S. Supreme Court in 2008.
Republican authorities rushed to extend the procedure to other states.
Over the past two years, they have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present photo IDs.
It should be noted that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million of voting age, do not own any photo ID issued by their state government.
Further, about five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an ID.
In addition, the required ID often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people on low incomes.
25% African-Americans, 15% of those with incomes below $35,000; As a result, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their affinity for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use their school-issued photo ID in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who are more likely to vote for Republican candidates to use the cards issued by those clubs during elections.
Until 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona introduced the first such requirement.
Since 2011, about a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes from the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers supported laws in eight states that abolish voter registration on Election Day.
In addition, they restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who want to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register around 10 million people.
However, the measures taken after 2009 caused a 17% drop in the registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers then passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the early election period.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, African-Americans made up 33% of early voters, even though only 13% of African-American voters in that state were African-American.
It was the same with Hispanics.
They made up only 11% of all voters, but 24% of citizens voting in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who accounted for 76% of all voters, accounted for only 46% of early voters.
Of course, the passage of laws that restrict voter registration was strongly opposed by democratic legislators and their supporters.
Democratic governors blocked several bills with their vetoes.
In order to suspend the most controversial laws, the Attorney General of the United States even intervened.
They managed to limit some of the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring photo ID.
However, the new rules will undeniably make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics have cited bias in the laws passed as an apparent effort to influence the outcome of the 2012 election in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states where these laws have passed account for 171 of the 270 electoral college votes necessary to win a presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is already certain: these new provisions will have an adverse impact on voter turnout.
