Detecting prostate cancer: to undergo an examination or not?
The PSA test yielded erroneous results that were incorrectly negative or even incorrectly positive, leading to unnecessary medical interventions.
All this increased the hesitancy of the men, who were already so reluctant to go for the examination at all.
To get tested or not?
We asked two experts for their opinion.
Studies conducted in the USA showed high levels of contamination between the different test groups, making it difficult to interpret these results and make valuable recommendations.
Another study, this time a European one, found a difference in mortality between patients who underwent examinations and those who did not.
This study also showed after a 12-year gap that those who do not go for the examination have a 30 to 40% higher risk of metastasis.
So I recommend testing from the age of 50 or from the age of 40 if your direct relative had prostate cancer.
African-American men are also a more vulnerable group.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer is detected.
There are aggressive cancers and those that are inert.
It is therefore necessary to correctly explain to the patient the extent of the danger of his type of cancer, to offer him possible alternatives, not necessarily to treat prostate cancer, which does not have a long-term impact on life, and to focus in these cases rather on active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer are not treated because their type of cancer is not aggressive and life-threatening.
Rather, we will suggest active surveillance and offer them treatment in case of disease progression.
Increasingly, and with greater precision, we are establishing criteria that help us decide which species to treat and which not.
Nevertheless, I recommend that you undergo the examination.
However, it is important to have an interview with a doctor and determine whether it is appropriate to undergo the examination or not.
