Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a rightful stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all the matter in the universe.
Furthermore, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is not yet one hundred percent certainty among physicists that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson as predicted by the Standard Model.
New data released this week during the major physics congress in Kyoto tend to confirm this, but all the data are still lacking to be absolutely certain.
However, suppose it is a Higgs boson, since the risks of error appear to be small, and let's look at what it is.
In this world there is an absolutely unquestionable law according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule can not be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies: the Pauli exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state", roughly speaking, creates some of their properties.
Furthermore, physicists divide particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently adhere to the Pauli principle.
And at the other end are bosons, vile anarchists who value nothing at all - certainly not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the (by the way, absolutely amazing) device that is The Particle Adventure at Berkeley Laboratories: mesons, which we will leave unnoticed here, and "force particles", which propagate the great forces of nature and with which the Higgs boson is probably related in some way.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it is thanks to a boson with an unusual banality: the photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "cancels" the electromagnetic field in that particular place, like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" gives rise to an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore one of the bosons, the "carriers of power".
More stable field
It is also the case with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that another field, the Higgs field, is necessary to "cancel" it, for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; To excite it, it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, similar to the frozen surface of a pond, which is only disturbed by a very large boulder.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge part accelerator as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - the Large Hadron Collider with friendly beams is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
The electromagnetic field analogy is again useful to explain the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Not all particles or all materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to the fridge by itself.
And it is also true that not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let's look at it) do not.
And Mrs. Novak asks, what are all this research for, what will it "bring us"?
From a scientific point of view, it confirms the validity of the Standard Model (SM), allowing physicists to examine any discrepancy between SM observations and predictions.
Moreover, quite a few physicists literally wish that they could be found, because the slightest difference could open the door to "new physics" and close some of the gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge flaws, it does not provide any explanation of gravity (oh!) or dark matter, which makes up approximately 80% of the cosmic matter (oh again!).
However, CERN has not yet discovered such discrepancies.
Repercussions
The repercussions of these surveys in the everyday lives of Mr. and Mrs. Novák are very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
See: in the early '60s, the pioneers of the Bell Labs laser had no idea of the revolution their work would generate.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (the previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said it - the laser was initially considered such a "lab toy".
Just imagine...
In addition, all the tools that surround research can also come into play.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle did not plan it at first, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that activities around the LHC necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that one really never knows...
Palliative care - The best way to leave life... | Le Devoir
Through its Commission on Dying with Dignity, Quebec recently became involved in the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is expected to continue shortly, and a bill is being drafted at the same time.
Much remains to be done in this crucial area.
Le Devoir tried to look at this question in more detail.
Less than a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him gave him a two-year reprieve.
"They gave me five years to live, and it's been seven," he says emotionlessly in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the previous day.
"It's still a shock, you can't prepare for this," he adds.
The illness has done its work: extreme weakness makes it impossible for him to go to the toilet alone or even to eat himself.
He looks resignedly at the tasty-looking breakfast and agrees that we will help him eat.
He is brave and even smiles, talks to strangers who stop by his place, bring him medicine, offer him a bath.
Courage for ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to get rid of the diarrhea, it humiliates me," she says.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
"All your life you learn that guys urinate standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois facility.
To return to the baby stage is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the abilities of each person" whether he accepts the return, the psychologist says.
In the opinion of many palliative care professionals, crucial moments take place at the very heart of such a return.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
Their prognosis is a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses who care for them does not provide them with so-called "medical" care.
In the case of Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "of suffocation while fully conscious."
But the disease allowed me to discover my children.
"I have good kids," he adds.
"I don't have any more wishes in my life," she says, and then she agrees to be put on a breathing apparatus.
Nevertheless, he is still looking forward to the last visit of his son from Italy in the coming days.
At the Victor-Gadbois Home, body care is provided with the help of nutrition in collaboration with a group of volunteers.
This is what palliative care looks like when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
This is very little if we realize that we will all die at some point.
Here, life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the home.
Whether it's a level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, he can be given, for example, a sip of brandy or pepsi, to taste.
Diabetics no longer have to watch their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life here.
Last night they brought beer to Mr. X, who died later that night.
This morning, his son will finish his beer in honor of his late father.
"We help patients as well as their loved ones," says Nathalie Savard, director of the care service.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, the days go one after another, but they do not resemble each other.
Next to a ninety-three-year-old man who rejoices in his last meeting with his family, thoroughly cushioned on pillows while they toast in his honor, a tragically thirty-six-year-old man dies, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children after trying every possibility to survive.
"For six months now, there have always been three to five beds for people with cancer under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who come to Victor-Gadbois come from their homes, 47% from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is designed to alleviate suffering once the patient reaches the final stage of their lives, whether it is at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Grand Montreal Home Palliative Treatment Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
It is this fundamental lack of access to health care in Quebec that has led many palliative care doctors to fear the adoption of a law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by leaders in the field of palliative treatment, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has access to quality palliative care before euthanasia can be agreed to.
She says she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in tremendous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
He is concerned that patients will ask for death because they do not receive appropriate care.
At the same time, many oncologists take care of their patients until the last moments, regardless of the unfavorable prognosis.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were minimal when she left the demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was quitting treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was stopping fighting, she told us.
And she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their treating doctors for not granting their wishes when the palliative pussy team relieved their pain.
However, it must be said that palliative care is definitely not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Grand Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients resist pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives that put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either in bursts or permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
A patient who is not relieved of pain will increasingly have access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not sedated always say the same thing: "I want to die."
But this doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me", it means "I want you to relieve my pain."
