In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are current account ledger depositories, controllers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
In fact, each transaction between two users takes place between two electronic addresses using e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of current accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key stage is to write this new transaction in this ledger.
It is done by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, whose solver, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the right to write this additional line.
This is the stage of cutting the file; i.e. the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital imprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then "chop up" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily check its correctness.
The transaction then appears indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; Any modification would alter the imprint.
If the user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes) for the purpose of fraud, the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the second will be abandoned, since each of them has a different fingerprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly divided by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they can be divided into up to one hundred millionths, so there is room for margin...
The difficulty of the task also increases with increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin were hacked and stored bitcoins were stolen.
"The loophole is not about the protocol itself," said Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also checks money laundering opportunities thanks to this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Major players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed a current account book and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins are out of circulation.
In November, "huge discounts" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payments, but uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions that make them cheaper.
In addition, the bearer manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up at retailers where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
All you have to do is give an address that can be "photographed and recognised" by phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that it already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems and move to more horizontal systems.
"It will take a while for Bitcoin to break through, but 2013 could be a decisive year," he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are currently considered elevated if this type of money is successful.
