Difficult work on the Egyptian constitution
President Mohamed Morsi embarked on another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history over the promulgation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to gamble.
On Wednesday, regardless of the opinion of everyone else, he announced that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text the next day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave this assembly an additional two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, which has been amended many times, which weakens the country's constitutional stability and leads to legal disputes.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country's divisions.
From the point of view of the opposition, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium," continuing to "break his word" and "trample on the law."
But his supporters say it is a means of tackling the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in two weeks' time.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Society to abandon its intention to clarify the text to the Egyptians article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy while protests are rocking the country.
As he confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor.
Especially since this hastily organised vote presents the Egyptian people with an ultimatum: 'Either you approve my text or I will retain unlimited powers', which should otherwise expire once the new constitution is approved.
And in this strange atmosphere, 85 deputies of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly yesterday, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the constitution was promulgated, they slammed the door, saying that they had no way of asserting their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities have imitated their move.
In order to reach a quorum, 11 substitutes were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, articles of the constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators went on to point out that one of the few controversies that day revolved around... hours for prayer, when some members of the committee were of the opinion that the clock in the meeting room was not properly adjusted.
The text voted on as recently as yesterday evening consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains identical to the 1971 version of the Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia law shall be the primary source of law."
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental demands, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," argue liberals, who see it as nothing more than a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular on issues of checking the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Sophie Pommier, an expert on Egypt, this is disturbing because "those called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This can be seen as the beginnings of a theocracy."
Liberals' fears are further fueled by the fact that the university's next president should be less moderate than the current one.
"So far, there has been no concrete religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulamas but university workers, many of them studied in French schools," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a paper on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be disagreements over the interpretation of Article 220 because the terms used in it belong to religious vocabulary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question may arise to what extent civil judges are competent to have a say on this."
In addition to the religious aspects, the text approved yesterday is highly criticised because of the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that they have been significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: powers vested in the military.
In accordance with the wishes of military officials, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, trials of civilians will not be banned in military courts, as requested by human rights groups.
These associations speak of their doubts in relation to a text which they consider to be directed against freedom.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is still prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, in particular for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, points out Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In its view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to address a televised address last night, rallies are planned for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then demonstrate on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the navel of the world and the sea made of a saturated salt solution are waiting for Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort, and the untouched nature of nature.
AaF has identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Bowing to Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that God's mercy descends on all who enter this "bath."
And Galilee - the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling with nets.
Here also Jesus appeared to his disciples and after the resurrection.
But most of the holy places are in Jerusalem.
The faithful will walk through the Way of Sorrows or the Way of Jesus (Via Dolorosa in Latin).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the trial took place, passes through the streets of the Old City and leads to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - to the place of crucifixion, to the stone of anointing and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the site where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew, from which they made a cross for Jesus' crucifixion.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site for Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a vertical journey
The ruins of the fortress of Masada remained from a secret hiding place from the enemy that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 BC.
The ruins are located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are engaged in mountaineering can get to it with their own hands.
Others will be taken to this historic mountain by cable car.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m there is the famous ski resort Hermon, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
A shuttle bus takes tourists to this ski paradise from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are around 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as approximately 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel-Aviv is also worth a visit.
His canvases include the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Acre, you can visit the museum-baths of Al Basha, which presents visitors with several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with dummies of bath users and spa keepers from that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire the statues of Dali and Roden.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are strictly refused.
The fifth museum - the Holocaust Museum, or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells of one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You step inside - and you find yourself in total darkness.
The stars glitter.
And the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they perished are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improve your health
The three main spa resorts of Israel are located on the coasts of the Mediterranean, Red Sea and Dead Seas.
Each offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, in the Red Sea it is possible to bathe even in the winter months, because the water temperature in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius, and the air heats up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and in it people bathe all year round.
The Dead Sea, by the way, is the most peculiar sea in the world, it is located at the lowest land point of the planet - at the level of 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated saline solution that easily keeps on the surface even people who do not know how to swim.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo treatment using salt water - brine, and healing mud, which can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to heal disheveled nerves.
Touch the mysterious distant past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through them passed the famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
Mentions of this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists really love to wander through the narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you press against the walls in the aisle of "your" sign, luck will be favorably inclined to you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come from all over Israel and even other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully renovated theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, for a word
Going to Israel, you can not worry about its imperfect English: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
On the way, it is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is approximately 3.8 shekels).
Public transport is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is served by high-speed trams, and Haifa is the country's only metro line with six stations connecting the lower city with the upper one.
Basically, it is an underground funicular railway.
Travel by all public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can travel 1.5 hours with a change.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, work stops at markets, shops and public transport.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels, you get only kosher food: except pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes containing a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a large selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, various kinds of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many fattened cats that gracefully "roam according to their taste".
In the evening, you can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Spinning cats love crowded places and enjoy any delicacy.
Car rental will cost from $ 37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $ 188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day, depending on the car brand.
Plus insurance - $ 15 per day.
And renting a bike will cost about 15 shekels per day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Expressed in numbers
In 2012, Israel was visited by more than three million tourists from all over the world.
Most citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine came to explore the country and relax.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
The "great and powerful" will announce it to Moscow: emigrants will save money for language
While MPs and human rights defenders are still debating the law on compulsory language exams, fraudsters have already appeared in the country selling "forged" certificates
13 million foreign workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities every year.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenia.
Their only goal is to earn enough money to support families at home.
On December 1, a law came into force, according to which every working migrant will be required to pass an exam in knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service sector, housing and municipal management, lifestyle and retail.
However, the FMS promises that in time the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the basics of law.
Knowledge of the language will also need to be confirmed in order to obtain and renew a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is an official language.
Even people who successfully managed to obtain attestation and obtain an academic diploma before the collapse of the USSR in 1991 are not subject to this law.
Benefit, condemnation and protection of rights
The network of test sites will work under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of Friendship between Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take exams in all cities; already today more than 160 such centers are opened in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by deputies of the State Duma and the FMS (Federal Migration Service).
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders were able to ask the question many times in the press: what will this actually bring?
What will change the obligation to know the language for Russians and for the visitors themselves?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service reply, this will make it possible to reduce the number of people who suffer as a result of "slave labor."
Many people today talk about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, Chairman of the Board of FMS of Russia in Tajikistan.
Protection of their rights should start before their departure.
Only a system of organised recruitment will make it possible to solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for emigrants without a profession, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowledge of the language, says Sebelev with conviction, the would-be migrant is doomed to clashes with dishonest people who, under the pretext of help, will provide him with a "voucher" to terrible, tight hostels in which he and dozens of others like himself will languish for months without food or documents and toil for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrant workers.
"In their homeland, they promise them one thing, but upon arrival they cheat them, confiscate their passports, do not pay the promised wages," confirms Tolib Sharipov, head of the Main Tajik Directorate of Labor Migration at the MS.
Don't swear!
Still less so because many citizens of the Central Asian republics who intend to go to work in Russia recognize that not only do they not know the language of the country they want to get to, but they do not even have experience with the job.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as their misfortune: very few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive at least a reasonable basic education.
After all, their families also need to feed their children with something, not to mention the fact that they need to be dressed, dressed and equipped for school decently.
As children reach working age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language, it is difficult - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
It is true that, with regard to the law on language examinations, human rights defenders point out one important point.
Testing will only be carried out on those migrants who have legal status.
If they don't, they won't take exams or get any other official jobs.
Meanwhile, most migrant workers continue to live illegally in Russia.
"Welcome, or Unauthorized Entry Forbidden"
Many of the incoming workers claim that getting official status in our country is not easy.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all those language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
Employees of the Russian police know that we basically have false documents, without registration, and this results in cases of blackmail.
"They require a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," - shared with journalists about his experience a citizen of Tajikistan Umed Khushkadamamov.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the language law, it was discovered that not only migrants' registration documents were false.
FMS employees have already confiscated several fake certificates of passing a language exam.
Counterfeit documents are printed on an ordinary colour printer.
Of course, they did not get to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, hoping to make it easier for themselves to pass the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times higher than passing the official test: it will cost migrant workers three thousand rubles.
The main task of the immediate future is to secure the system against corruption, so that workers cannot simply buy documents, government officials and human rights defenders agree.
Meanwhile, government authorities can promise foreign workers who failed the tests the first time needed time to take a course in the basics of the Russian language.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas where active dealings with people are not required.
MVD (Ministry of the Interior) does not circulate the illegal arms market
