Fast food and supermarket workers on strike in the US
Up to a quarter of all American teenagers go through work at the cash desk of "McDonald's" establishments
In recent days, a wave of protests against low wages has risen in Walmart hypermarkets and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as "McDonald's", "Burger King", "Taco Bell", "Wendy's" and "Kentucky Fried Chicken".
So far, no one can predict whether this wave will turn into the ninth wave, or whether it is destined to disappear soon.
The whole event is supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing social organizations.
In addition to the meager pay increases that ordinary workers at Walmart and fast-food systems receive, the goal of the protest organizers is to create them in their unions.
At present, this economic sector is virtually untouched by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The action began last week after Thanksgiving, on so-called "Black Friday," when an of cheap sales hit America, engulfing millions and in some cases accompanied by brawls.
On this day, some workers at Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their workplaces and demonstrated together with unions and left-wing activists of multinational chain stores whose goods are intended for people from the lower and middle classes.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk all over the world.
Products in its stores are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That's why many low-wage employees at Walmart stores only shop at their place of work.
The availability and assortment of goods have made Walmart one of the largest companies in America.
Critics say Walmart can afford to sell goods so cheaply in part because it pays its employees so little.
They also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of automatic carts or handheld scanners.
"Black Friday" protesters demanded pay rises and complained that the cost of health insurance provided by the company had risen sharply from $30 to $100 a month.
The typical Walmart worker is paid $9.5 an hour, but that's not commensurate with expenses, employees say.
Researchers at the University of California, Berkeley, show that if Walmart raises the average wage to $12 an hour, it will cost the company $3.2 billion a year.
That's an average of 1.1% more than this company spends on salaries now.
If Walmart shifts the wage increase entirely onto consumers' shoulders, each visit to the store will cost only 46 cents more.
In a year, customers will spend approximately $12.39 more than today.
Walmart's advocates point out that the protest took place in only nine countries and should cause virtually no harm to the company.
"Black Friday" in the company's stores lasted from 8 p.m. Thursday until midnight the next day, and during that time Walmart sold about 5,000 items of merchandise per second.
In total, its coffers made nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
Company representative Dan Fogelman said in an interview with the left-leaning Huffington Post website that a total of "fewer than five" Walmart employees had left their jobs, and that the protest was "another media sensation" orchestrated by the union.
"Unoccupied cash register!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their target was not Walmart department stores (which are not very popular in the progressive city and therefore almost are not there), but "McDonald's" and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's says it sells billions of servings, and then it doesn't even pay you sick pay and doesn't pay you properly for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, New York City Council Member
Currently, the minimum wage for work under federal law and New York state regulations is $7.25 per hour.
Fast-food restaurants are gradually increasing this wage, but only slightly, and on average their regular workers in New York are paid $8.90 an hour.
In this expensive city, no one has a lower wage.
I don't quite understand how you can exist in New York for that kind of money.
Employment at "McDonald's" goes through nearly a quarter of American teenagers who work part-time behind the counter after school and live with their parents.
Few people see it as their main source of livelihood or plan to stay there for long.
At present, I constantly meet in conversation with "McDonald's" workers who complain that they have to live off this money and sometimes even feed their children from it.
On the other hand, there is a comment on the Wall Street Journal forum whose author notes that it's irresponsible to have children if you don't know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. Thursday outside "McDonald's" on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and cooks at fast-food outlets begin receiving at least $15 an hour, more than double their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that trade unions be established in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing the formation of trade unions and punishing union activists with harassment and dismissal.
On the other hand, management rarely makes their lives easier.
However, it is also difficult to introduce trade unions in fast food outlets for objective reasons.
One of the main reasons is the unusually high staff turnover.
Disagreement
On that day, noisy protests were also held in a number of other budget Manhattan restaurants.
The culmination of this event was a rally at noon at "McDonald's" near Times Square, where several local Democratic politicians, notably city council member Jumaane Williams, spoke and said, "McDonald's says it sells billions of servings, and then it doesn't even pay you sick pay and it doesn't pay you properly for your honest work!"
The demonstrators also received support from other prominent New York Democrats, such as mayoral candidate Bill de Blasio, who said that "we must stand together in support of fast-food workers so that they can achieve the fair pay for their work and the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!"
As the New York Times described it, it was the largest event of its kind in the history of the American fast food industry.
But only a few hundred people participated, although not all of them were fast food employees, which employ tens of thousands of people in New York.
Whether this event will become the spark that will ignite the flame of the mass movement is still unclear.
"So far, the brain has been deceived mediocrely"
Among fans of modern virtual reality technologies, the topic of augmented reality is popular; Recently, this means perceiving the world mainly through the prism of special glasses.
At its annual conference earlier this summer, Google demonstrated a working model of the novelty, and in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed for the patent.
An interview with Sharam Izadi, head of Microsoft's interactive 3D technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge Lab, shows that for the company's scientists, glasses are a thing of the past.
They are attracted by the perspective of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, creating virtual public spaces.
- Please tell us in general terms what your research group does?
- We deal with human-machine interactions, but at the same time we try to push the boundaries of this interaction.
Meanwhile, humanity is stuck in the stage of working with pixels on a flat screen, at most sometimes touching the screen with a finger.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead and anticipate significant changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors - this is a step forward, and almost no Xbox today is on sale without Kinect sensors, because for everyone there is a very interesting option to control with gestures.
- What else awaits us in the future?
- Despite the fact that Kinect has brought interaction to the physical level, a lot of interactions still take place on flat screens, sometimes in 3D.
The input flow of information has improved (the system receives more data), but the output flow is not yet very good.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional imaging systems based on various technologies, including projective ones.
We need to let the computer world into our physical world, make it more real.
However, for this it is necessary to know not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we will be able to add virtual objects to the real world in a much more appropriate form.
And first of all - to hell with those stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
This is a popular thing, but is it not overrated?
- It certainly cannot be considered a panacea - the issue of privacy arises, because we do not always want to inform others around us about our activities and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but in their own environment.
For example, for controlling devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not sweeping, just such stingy, short ones.
The gestures would not be captured by the device's camera, but by a bracelet that would track the movements of bones and muscles.
So far, it is large, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future has a mixed type of control, for example, gesture + voice.
- And how?
- For example, how do you ask me to give you this can of soda?
You say it and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that will be very difficult to recognize.
- So you want to get users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at any given moment?
- This is not necessary at all, but it is a rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the development of new types of sensors that can more accurately detect human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, which provide a fairly good depth resolution, this is very important.
- If you have to talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your requirements for modern cameras?
Isn't there enough resolution, depth, or something else today?
- Basically, the current generation - this is what we can reflect on in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at 1000 f/s.
But it's not just about the megapixels themselves, but as matrices and depth.
Looking at things today, all current technologies are insufficient for us - this adds work to algorithm designers.
So we must bear in mind not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also the Z.
So the speed, the number of frames per second, is also very important.
Human movement is quite dynamic, and current data streams of 30 frames per second are, frankly, a bit low, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes from our laboratory in Redmond made a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms, with current, mass-produced sensors closer to the second value (60-100 ms).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
For me, the equivalent of such a device would be very useful at work, I just don't need so many touches, but I need some extra frames per second.
- And increasing the number of cameras is not necessary?
- Three "cameras" are now used in Kinect, one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other - a receiver of the reflected signal.
And already the third camera - this is actually a common visible band sensor.
This is not used to determine the depth of an object.
A larger number of cameras could potentially solve the problem...
Or make it worse, because it would increase the necessary volume of calculations performed.
It would be nice to create a flexible analog Kinect system, play with the curvature of camera placement, and see how it helps in determining three-dimensional positioning.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft (unlike Google) did not publicly present its glasses.
Don't you think that when it comes to the day-to-day use of augmented reality technology using special glasses, this is one of the most promising platforms?
- Of course, walking around while constantly holding the smatphone in your hands is not very comfortable, but I think: the strongest option would be a "portable" form of reality augmentation, where it would be possible to switch at any time from glasses to a smartphone, projection screen and further around based on the clouds platform.
Glasses - this is a very personal device, this is their strength (private things can be seen only by you), and at the same time also weakness - augmented reality on the basis of glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects simultaneously with other people.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark in "Iron Man", but also to ordinary mortals.
There is one problem that critics often point out: there is no touch response!
Hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality - this is the seventh consecutive breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the addition of tactile sensations could easily become the eighth breakthrough.
So far, one of the interesting tricks is used - the use of the second hand as a kind of background for imaging.
Excellently records compressions!
But there are also technologies that are really aimed at adding tangibility to these "images in the air" – for example, the interference of several directional ultrasound beams at a defined point where the finger is located produces a tactile sensation, but it is still very faint – as if you were blowing on your fingertips.
There is also a bracelet on the wrist, which affects the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool your brain?
To think that he feels what he seems to feel in the moment when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried that yet.
Here there is yet another challenge that will be fought for a long time - how to get a person who is physically in a very confined space to believe that he is walking through open, practically infinite space - we are also working on the concept of running tracks (not at all like in clubs), a moving platform and also huge balls.
If deception of the brain becomes the goal, then the work is still for many years.
This is what makes working on virtual reality so appealing to researchers – many things are in their infancy.
