Giving birth in space
The country is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with earthlings on board embark on a journey, looking for an alternate planet.
In order to save humanity, the main question arises: how to keep their species in weightlessness or on a given alternate planet?
I think the choice is not great.
In fact, there are only two planets that can be mastered, if only hypothetically.
"It's Venus and Mars," says Vladimir Surdin, a high-ranking scientist at the P.K. Sternberg State Astronomical Institute (SAISH).
But while there are better conditions for life on Mars, temperatures on the surface of Venus reach temperatures of 500 degrees Celsius.
It is possible to live there only at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
To solve the issues of reproduction in space, scientists began with flora.
Already half a century ago, experiments on plants were carried out.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit are no different from their terrestrial relatives.
After that, the launch of insects into orbit was carried out - very small fruit flies Drosophila.
In 1979, a quail egg was sent into space to see how an embryo develops in weightlessness.
At the exit we get an absolutely normal bird.
But then the problems begin.
"The problem arises with the fact that this bird has to find a foothold, it has to stand on its own feet and start moving," says the head of the laboratory of the Institute of Biomedical Problems (IBMP) RAN Vladimir Sychev.
If they do not find a foothold, the birds fall chaotically and do somersaults.
After 10 hours, the newly hatched birds experienced a complete extinction of instincts.
The birds did not react to light or sound.
And the trouble was, they simply perished within four days.
"We let birds hatch twice, but then we refused, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychev comments on the failure of the experiment with chickens in space.
The last "mini-ark" with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
In the spring of 2013, the experiments will continue.
But in the biosatellite "Bion" there will be only beings of one sex.
There was an experiment with rats that were already pregnant when sent into space.
Basically, they didn't discover anything supernatural there.
"It was only on biosatellites, but again - this is a unique experiment and such experiments need to be conducted," says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing on earth, offspring was born to space rats.
However, it has not yet been possible to approach the problem of reproduction directly in space.
It is a difficult task.
Animals in the loss of the usual habitat simply can not realize their sexual instinct.
Man, unlike animals, in principle can.
Homo sapiens possesses abstract thinking and is able to create an appropriate emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The greatest danger threatened Tereshkova.
