SAO chief: Control of the Švarc system failed through the fault of politicians
The Czech Republic has good inspectors and high-quality legislation in connection with public procurement, but it lags behind in its application.
Miloslav Kala, Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office, says this in an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - this is what I think is missing in our country," Kala said.
Similar conclusions are also suggested by a joint inspection of Czech and German auditors.
As an example of incorrect practice, he cites Petr Nečas's approach to the so-called "Švarc system".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS will not bother entrepreneurs with its inspections - is it therefore prohibited or permitted?
"After all, the law must be set up somehow, and if he prohibits something, then even the prime minister cannot prevent the activities of an office that has the duty to go to check and enforce duties," Kala said.
At the meeting of the Audit Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German sides, within which legislation concerning public procurement in both countries was compared.
What exactly was it about?
This is a parallel control that we started about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation regulates how to deal with public procurement, followed by individual national legislation and then by practice itself.
We put all this together, and although the inspection is not yet complete, we have seen very interesting differences - generally speaking, legislation in our country is perhaps "stricter and more perfect", but the practice itself is better in Germany in some parameters.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, but it is necessary to pay attention to the actual application of the law.
What can this project actually help you for, what does it mean for you?
It is precisely such joint control that could help us to stop making efforts to refine laws, reduce and improve limits, when it does not have such a positive impact.
Thrift means obtaining the appropriate thing at a reasonable (but not always the lowest) price, in order to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal conduct.
But by lowering the contract limit, we don't necessarily achieve that.
Perhaps the system will be overloaded with so much "paper" that those who want to look for holes in the system will draw from it much more easily than if the limit remained higher.
You talk about domestic problems with the transposition of public procurement legislation into practice.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an office similar to our SAO, or is it set up differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the Bundesrechnungshof works there as the SAO, which is organised similarly to us, it also has a college, but it is formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both offices proceed similarly.
The powers are also somewhat similar, but since Germany has a federal structure, it also has these courts of audit at the level of the individual Länder - this is where the system differs a little from ours.
BRH can only control federal money, represented in our country by state resources.
Public funds, which are administered by regions and municipalities in our country, are audited there from the level of the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for the legislation there, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare it without specific data, but in some respects Germany is referred to as a model, but it cannot be said for sure that it is better in everything.
Is it because they have better controllers?
Certainly not, but again, I don't like such comparisons.
But it has to be said that even the countries that we consider to be a model face a number of problems.
Otherwise, it would not be of any benefit to them to cooperate with our office, right?
As far as domestic legislation is concerned, what did the amendment to the Public Procurement Act mean for your office, are its impacts already manifested?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it is not yet reflected in our control actions.
Since we carry out ex-post checks, there is a certain delay to be expected.
So far, we have only observed this in the process of preparing future inspections - we have launched our new tool "detection of risks of inefficiency", through which we have swept almost 14,000 public contracts, and we have analysed them - there the changes will naturally be reflected, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tenders will be adjusted, and so on.
Do you consider the approval of this law to be a benefit or an additional burden on the system by bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction, and I hope that it will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise here is that the rules will be "tightened" and it will not be possible to comply with them.
Already during the operation of the previous rules, the inspected persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the regional council) to the fact that any failure to comply with the Public Procurement Act constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it worth tightening up the law in this way?
I think not in this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, and not punish those who commit formal errors that have no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only put more pressure on the bureaucracy.
So how to get out of it?
Let's see where the road does not lead.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS will not bother entrepreneurs with inspections of the so-called "Švarc system" - and what does this mean?
Is the Švarc system forbidden or allowed?
After all, the law must be set up somehow, and if he prohibits something, then not even the Prime Minister can prevent the activities of an office that has the duty to go and check and enforce duties.
He can say, "We're going to change the law and allow it," but he can't say we're going to do nothing.
In the Public Procurement Act, there are relatively strict rules on how things are to be formally carried out - which is right, in order to protect the public tender.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the bidder with the best offer is excluded only because of formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - that is what I think is missing in our country.
