Šimon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at concerts
What do you think about the end of the world coming in less than a month?
It's just one more scaremongering that we humans like to grab hold of.
Together with The Tap Tap we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also organize an absolutely unique project called Three Concerts Against the End of the World.
Can you introduce it to readers?
It is a nationwide benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to use the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 am.
The day before, on December 20 at 9 p.m., 3 concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is 12 hours ahead of us in the time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Originally it was probably my idea, then we came up with everything together with our artist Honza Augusta.
In addition to the fact that we want to gather enough positive energy and prevent the end of the world, we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we will one day pass this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also created a unique collection of items, shoes, T-shirts, bags or original keys against the end of the world, which people can also support us by buying on www.e-tap.cz.
The Tap Tap band, along with other artists, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, called "The End of the World Canceled".
It is already very popular on YouTube, will it also be heard at these benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, that is, if we succeed and the end of the world does not come...
It will be sung by all performers at all three concerts simultaneously.
The anthems will suddenly be interconnected in a unique live broadcast on Czech Television.
The words to this song were written and the main role of Jesus in the clip is played by Tomáš Hanák, Xindl X also sings in it...
How did you get to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, as we organize a lot of benefit events and concerts...
We try to involve them intensively in these projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested and enjoy working with us.
What will the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world go to?
To equip the barrier-free educational center Studeo, which we have been implementing for six years with the Tap civic association in the Jedlička Institute.
Students of the Jedlička Institute schools are regularly visited by lecturers and devote themselves to activities that they enjoy and are interested in.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to the lecturers themselves, so we try to enable them to do so in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building will be built in the future, to which we will move with this project.
Each concert will feature several bands and performers.
How did you choose them?
We tried to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform in Prague.
Full details can be found on www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any similar "bombastic events" in the future?
In May, we will perform at the Prague Spring Festival for the first time, so we will certainly prepare an interesting program with interesting guests here as well.
Next year we would also like to play at the Czech National House in New York, and I personally, when we are in the USA, I would like to combine it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not minimalist, so far you have performed for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group made up of handicapped people.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It is not as terrible as it seems at first glance.
We have five members on an electric wheelchair, their trolleys have to travel in the luggage compartment, and of course we carry a large amount of cargo and crates with tools...
However, so far it has always been managed without any problems, CSA and British Airways were so well prepared for us that I was often surprised.
Even in Moscow, from which we returned recently, it was without problems.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare how individual ones differ in barrier-free accessibility, public access to the handicapped and so on.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than in our country, we have witnessed in Russia that everything in the East is still at its very beginnings.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is very barrier-free, here it is still unusual for a person in an electric wheelchair to move alone in the city center.
There are no such commonplaces as giving way to a wheelchair user in an elevator.
Fortunately, civic associations are already emerging there that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And what, on the contrary, do we still have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things where we are still behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation is always dependent on the efforts of the people involved.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common that even people with severe disabilities move independently in public, they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
However, it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to actively participate in social life, on the contrary, we are a bit ahead with The Tap Tap!
Respecting the public or being wheelchair accessible is one thing, but it's only when we become important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers that things really start to change.
So far, these are isolated cases of strong-willed people.
The Tap Tap band is currently very popular, but let's go back a few years, what made you start it in 1998?
I started working as an educator at the Jedlička Institute, where I was surrounded by many young people who were interested in doing something.
And since I am a musician myself, I play the saxophone, among other things, so together with a colleague I founded a music hobby group.
And over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, it got a bit out of hand (laughs).
But the popularity has only come in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that it helped us when we started to connect with well-known singers and also actively work on promoting the band.
We realized that work that is not visible basically does not exist.
Thanks to contributions from the European Union, we can also afford high-quality lecturers, equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to take The Tap Tap this high?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do something differently.
Show business is full of things where one imitates the other.
It is logical in a way, everything new is accepted cautiously and takes a long time.
Things that are unique are very few, but I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is, of course, regret, that is natural...
But that pity is completely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not suffering from all abandoned beings that we have to pity.
These are people who can live a full life and develop, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means to do so.
I say that when people with disabilities succeed in something, it is not just a shift for them, but for the whole society.
Has this success been helped by being a strict boss, as many people have labeled you?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising in many things and require a certain discipline.
But I think that's perfectly normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic idea and their heads in the clouds, and when they find out that they have to go to rehearsals twice a week, attend prep and spend a lot of time traveling to concerts, the enthusiasm quickly leaves them.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and that wants to achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there when it started in 1998?
Only one Lada Angelovic.
We are an open group, people come and go, this cannot be prevented.
Who has the will and desire, always has the door open with us
