Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, the second country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has been involved in a number of ESA projects over the years.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts had been involved in space flights before the Second World War; But they did not always meet with understanding.
I will recall, for example, the lecture of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, who on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Entry into Cosmonautics.
The thoughts of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsche Prize for Entry into Space in France.
The above-mentioned doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and astronautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of astronautics and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway trolley was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the design is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was intended to be used to start the trolley or to brake it.
Information about this trolley is known only from the period press.
Since 1933, Polish artillery began to deal with rocket missiles.
The research was carried out by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from the surviving materials that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, a proposal for a photoelectric fighter rocket designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the professional press, and in the following year the work Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza by Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) coordinated all the projects of military use of rocket technology.
The Committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activity was terminated by the start of war.
Other works devoted to astronautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The company was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of Problem magazine, which contained four more extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, by prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with astronautics.
At that time, projects of artificial satellites were already underway and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn the PTA became a full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been significantly involved in the development of the highly successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) weather rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a ceiling of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket began in the Bled Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next development type should already be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have a ceiling of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the altitude wind.
However, in 1962 further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, there was a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a volume of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C with a volume of 0.62 liters.
The maximum ceiling for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aerospace Institute developed the Meteor-2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch mass of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites under the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Abolishing the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court annulled the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively public debate.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU, as in a globalised world, are based on the principle of multiple, unregulated competition.
In effect, this means that individual economic formations, national economic systems, stand in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in the price of labour (wages), price tensions occur.
That term must be understood as a situation in which a producer tries to compete by importing cheap goods by 'undercutting' a competitor's price in order to gain a larger market share and thereby increase its own profits.
On a massive scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to transfer production abroad, or to buy there cheaply, or to disappear. The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it produces, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
The whole situation is aggravated by the complete unwillingness of the entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused by society as a whole in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that there is no need to give specific statistics.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create a situation in individual economies where the governments of individual countries are forced to enter into competition with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments put private capital at the risk of their own populations, regardless of social decline.
This is reflected primarily in changes in applicable laws.
The aim is to economically force its own population to accept the price dictates of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done both through a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment and through the restriction of workers' rights in the area of labour law.
The result is rising poverty, along with an increase in the gap between rich and poor.
In Germany, there have been public food dispensaries for the poor who cannot support themselves by their own work for many years.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
As part of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for duly employed people to receive such a wage that the state has to pay them up to the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal was also made public in the case of the auxiliary employees of the Bundestag.
Austerity measures in virtually all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation where people are forced either to emigrate, as was the case in the 19th century, or to languish on the margins of society on starvation wages, hoping that private investment capital will one day come to the country.
But here it is necessary to ask, where will it come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, or a Turk, a Moroccan, or an Egyptian, or an African, still works for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media claim ad nauseam that the state cannot participate in capital in its own economy, that a controlled economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital stubbornly insists that the state must not intervene in the economy through management intervention.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, now actually directs politics and thus the whole state in its own egoistic sense.
Here is the unequivocal answer that yes.
The proof is the existence of a virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the areas of corruption, mutual benefits, legislation, where practically everything is reprehensible but nothing criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that state ministries, due to lack of funds, outsource the drafting of laws to private law firms, which are often connected with industry.
These bills are then approved in the Bundestag.
All power thus does not come from the people, as Western-style constitutions proclaim, but from financially powerful groups that prefer their own interests.
It is evident that liberal-oriented democracies are now rapidly finding themselves in the situation described by Appian in his The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the Time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long been in complete disrepair, and offices were occupied by force.
For bribes, illegal gaining favor and with stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption were rampant, and the people went to the polls with a pre-sold vote" ..."people of character did not run for office at all, so that once, as a result of this disruption, the state was without consuls for eight months." .." Indeed, it began to be said that the only remedy in a bad situation was autocracy, and that it was necessary to elect an energetic man." Appian thought of Pompey, but it was Caesar who turned democracy into autocracy permanently.
Conclusion: As in antiquity, contemporary society is based on a ruthless preference for self-interest, regardless of society-wide interest.
Private capital, by its very nature, is incapable of understanding and asserting the benefit of society as a whole.
The result, now, as then, is an unprecedented decadence of elites without any attempt at deeper reforms.
The causality of the rise of both fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
As it stands, the demise of these systems in favor of liberal-style democracy can be seen as a pause in anticipation of the next round.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that the current elites are completely ignoring the possible loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, humanitarian and social disasters in the future, along with crimes against humanity as we know them from both old and modern history.
Abolishing the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of competition at both the international and intra-European levels, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution is targeted political-social reforms that will strengthen the capital participation of the state in the economy, strengthen the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
