Argo: When It's Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student demonstrators occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution to the US, which had been the patron of his regime for several decades.
For the US administration, the situation did not offer a positive way out - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it would fundamentally jeopardize the trust of allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages was not achieved in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later exacerbated by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations were mediated by the Algerian government.
Their plight has sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
Directed by actor Ben Affleck, Argo, describes an episode in that history that brought America a small victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six employees fled it.
After complicated twists and turns, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story - they left on Canadian passports as members of a film crew that inspected the locations for the filming of a sci-fi blockbuster in the country.
Combination of genres
The plan, devised by "exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the legend credible, the film project was written about in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, a fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have long been kept secret, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a strange combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time a so-called "caper movie", a story of a successful stunt, a sneak peek - an example is a series of Danny's sidekicks.
On the one hand, documentary-style sequences from Tehran change in the film (the title sequence shows iconic period photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were presented in the film - there are no big differences).
On the other hand, lighter passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and slight exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in suits discussing the situation at the negotiating tables, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed a career restart in remarkable fashion.
From a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director, and even his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, following the dark crime film Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller The City (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film that is not set in the director's home town of Boston.
A sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that elevated the director's older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck is showing it in Argos, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, reconstructing real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which at the same time conveys the emotion of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history suddenly moves somewhere.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake crew at a Tehran bazaar).
Too many things happen in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story being told does not actually offer much in the cinematic sense of thrilling scenes.
He works with it quite successfully, sometimes adding something to reality - everything does not work out so elegantly there (the scene in which the impending crisis at Tehran airport is averted by a phone call in America and a chase down the runway seems rather far-fetched).
But Argo's weakness is the restlessness resulting from the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming as Hollywood collaborators, but their characters deserve more space and are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film loses a bit of dramatic thrust, a film that can be watched with mild interest, appreciating the realization and retro style evoking the thrillers of the 70s.
But it's hard to pull down.
But it will suffice to remind us of a history that is still somewhat alive and a proof of how exaggerated the notions of all-powerful and omniscient secret services are.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com server, which annually announces a poll on the most absurd bank fee, has now decided to announce a competition for "the most absurd regulations or ideas from the EU".
"We were led to this by the last event, when the EU plans to adopt a 40 percent quota for women in the management of large European companies," Patrik Nacher, the organizer of the survey, told Pravo.
Among the nominated absurdities is, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify premium rates for men and women.
Until now, women have been favoured in the prices of life insurance policies because they are objectively less risky for insurance companies.
"More incredible ideas from the EU can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual voting will then take place until the end of February 2013," Nacher informed.
Controversial EU regulations include mandatory blending of biofuels into fuels, which is harmful to nature, a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain relatively small amounts of a dangerous substance, and a directive on the size of chicken cages, which has made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
Previously, he also faced criticism for a de facto ban on the use of the term pomazánkové máslo or the exclusion of incandescent bulbs from sale.
Quality bananas should have 14 centimeters
The EU apparatus often makes decisions under the pressure of one or another business or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by a state or group of states (so the Czech Republic now enforces the demands of its banks with the threat of a veto).
The interests of the Lobby were also behind the fact that, for example, bananas of the highest quality in the Union had to be at least 14 cm long and could not show 'anomalous curvature'.
The European Commission defended itself by saying that it was only harmonizing existing inconsistent national standards that had complicated trade.
The EU has already softened standards on fruit and vegetables, despite opposition from some countries, pointing out that existing directives lead to food waste.
A candidate for victory in the poll may also be last year's EU regulation, according to which inflatable balloons sold must be warned that children under 8 years of age must not inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU cited American research showing that balloons among toys are the leading cause of death for children from suffocation.
A similar restriction now applies to children under 14 years of age when blowing into fairground frkaky.
Curious ideas are born even at home
The rule concerning European officials themselves is also quite absurd - anyone who has an official position in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia due to the sensitivity of the topic for Greece and must instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, the Bankovnípoplatky.com server nominated for the survey, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a Member State.
The EU set the maximum volumes of food stocks that could be located in the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the Union.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the set volumes for canned mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a high fine.
The organizers of the survey were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea and the idea of awarding subsidies to apply for a subsidy.
However, these ideas did not originate in Brussels, but in Prague.
"We are handicapped by the fact that we do not have a sea.
We will ask the European Union for a refund," said then-Agriculture Minister Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he stated that a lot of grain was harvested in our country and as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the state should have full warehouses that it had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros for the fact that the Czech Republic is further away from the ports.
In the end, the European Commission accommodated the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The subsidy for obtaining the subsidy was offered to municipalities by the Ministry for Regional Development managed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), specifically they were supposed to go to write an application for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
Although regulations are easily criticised in the Member States, the EU's efforts to regulate and at the same time to make the functioning and development of the whole Union more effective deserve recognition, according to many experts.
According to experts, a more serious problem is, for example, drawing EU subsidies for projects that have no idea to do with deepening European integration, but which were forced by member states during budget negotiations.
Emotions among Czechs are also aroused by the fact that, like other EU countries, the Czech Republic has to fight in Brussels for the right to a specific designation of its traditional products, and it does not always succeed in this struggle.
Although the Czechs defended the name of Olomouc Tvarůžky after a six-year struggle with the Germans and Austrians, our producers had to rename the domestic rum, whose tradition dates back to the 19th century.
Only products made from cane spirit and not from sugar beet may bear the name rum.
The official list of registered EU products in the company of world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from Lübeck, Germany or Parma ham has already included Karlovy Vary biscuits, Pohořelický and Třeboň carp and Žatec hops.
The EU trademark can also be proud of Pardubice gingerbread and Hořice rolled wafers.
People want me to save the republic, but I'm an amateur, says Okamura
Senator, how does one get the idea that he wants to run for president?
I'm not interested in being a senator or president.
If it worked without problems in our country, I wouldn't be running anywhere.
But I can no longer watch the country stealing for the last twenty years, thieves running around, increasing taxes and retirement ages.
I had no ambition to be a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, I try to come up with a solution to change it.
And since I'm already forty and an independent non-partisan, I have no other way to influence things than to run for senator or president.
You got into the Senate, but soon you went to the Castle.
Aren't you turning your back on the people who elected you?
I have said all along that I will go into the fight for the Castle according to the result in the Senate elections.
I later clarified that if I was elected senator, I would run for president.
But my goal is not a function, a function is a tool for making my visions come true.
That is why I need as much influence and as strong a mandate as possible.
The trouble is not only that as a nation we curse in the pub and on TV, but that we trample on anyone who wants to try to change.
Add to this the media, which denigrates people and confuses freedom of speech with the freedom to lie.
For example, it was said about me that I bribed journalists or that I was an advisor to Jiří Paroubek.
Let's get to your visions.
You set out for the battle for the Castle with the thesis of material and criminal liability of politicians and retroactive property declarations over twenty million.
To do this, you need to change the law.
But as president, you don't have that power, and only the Senate as a whole can propose laws.
How do you want to solve this?
When, as a citizen, I lobbied for guiding to be a free trade, I managed to push it through.
The problem is politicking - when someone comes up with a good proposal from the left or the right, it is deliberately rejected, and this delays citizens.
As an independent non-partisan, I have much greater potential to gain support from all parliamentary parties.
My advantage is that without party pigeonholing and dogma, I can take something that is best for our country from each side and apply it.
Do you consider yourself more of a right-wing or left-wing person?
From the Czech point of view, it seems to me that people rank me more to the left.
For me, it doesn't matter at all whether it's a little to the left or a little to the right.
For me, it's important that we go forward.
I don't care whether someone belongs to the left or the right, but I want to bring people together.
I will always support any publicly good solution, even if it is proposed by the KSCM or ODS, and I will also be against a bad idea.
You get angry when someone calls you a populist.
But aren't you proving it by what you said?
When you create a business plan in a company, you also have an ideal goal and vision.
And that's what you're trying to get closer to.
Some may call it populism, but all the proposals I am talking about are already working in the world, or have been talked about by eminent experts.
But without the support of parliament, all you have to do is slogans.
And that's not enough in politics in the long run.
Or do you think that if you go to people and talk to them, you will succeed, for example, in enforcing criminal and material liability?
I have no choice.
Convincing politicians, journalists and the public and trying to get them on our side to get it through.
If I were elected President, there would be no problem in organising a live television broadcast where I would ask the chairmen of the parliamentary parties to legislate material and criminal liability for politicians, officials, judges and prosecutors.
And they might have to say why they don't want it.
When there is a strong personality who names abuses, one can push the political scene.
Take the direct election of the president, that was due to public pressure.
I say frankly that I am an amateur, that I am neither a genius nor an intellectual.
I try to find allies for my opinions and visions.
I have only just started in politics and I will try to get majority support for my program.
I try to move things myself, if it doesn't work, in six years I will quit and return to the private sector.
It sounds a bit like Okamura should save the Czech Republic.
I am no savior.
I know that I will not do anything in one person, so I went around a number of well-known people to see if they would also run for the Senate.
I went to see Radim Jančura, but he refused because of the amount of work.
At least that is how I supported the investigative journalist Jana Lorencová, who uncovered the fraud with light fuel oil.
I ran because people were really unhappy, but now I'm in the balance.
Sixty percent of the people did not vote, and those who did mostly elected representatives of the establishment.
There are only two independents in the Senate.
The people elected the Senate in such a way that changes will be difficult to enforce.
Nevertheless, I will fight for my visions, such as the direct election of mayors or governors.
Are you thinking about starting your own party?
I haven't thought about that yet, because I don't have time to check every potential partisan's background, and I don't have the money to do so.
I don't even have money for a presidential campaign, there are only 20,000 in my transparent account.
No money?
You're talking about asset declarations, what's yours?
I estimate private equity at about 60 million.
In Prague I have a plot of land for about 25 million, an apartment for ten million, another apartment for eight million, a collection of works of art for about ten million, an Aston Martin for 3.5 million and a Škoda Superb for a million, and then I have a few million in my account.
By the way, I have an Aston Martin because it was my boyhood dream - I always liked James Bond, who drove the car, was gallant to women and at the same time fought against bad things and abuses.
Do you drive an Aston Martin, have assets worth 60 million and have no money for a campaign?
You say you want to change the republic, but you don't want to put your own money into it.
This is not very convincing.
I don't have $15 million for a campaign.
Should I go into debt?
I've already put 2.5 million into the campaign.
The fact that I don't have any sponsors suggests that there is probably not so much interest in my program.
And I have no obligation to pay for the campaign out of my own pocket.
Basically, my campaign costs will be covered by what senator's salary I receive.
But I would not live on it, for example, I would not be able to pay my son for an English school, which costs 30 thousand a month.
If I just want to make money, I'm not running anywhere.
So you're going to keep doing business to live?
Didn't you say you would tone down these activities?
But this is not related to the amount of salary.
As promised, I have partially reduced my activities.
For example, my deputy will become the managing director of the travel agency in the spring.
People would like me to be a Samaritan who would save the Republic.
But I also need to live on something.
How much were you used to earning per month as an entrepreneur?
Two hundred to 400 thousand, which I take further.
And if I were president, I would shut down my business.
