The architects of MVRDV are proof that real adventures do not just take place in the head - for example, Spijkenisse and the recently built Mountain of Books - 2 images
"I find the building cheerful, it looks futuristic. There's finally something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, walking by the side of the road.
Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large nearby company, says, "Of course, the house is nice."
However, I ask why we still need a library today.
They all have internet, iPads and e-books.
No one volunteers to visit any of these old-style libraries anymore, does they?
Spijkenisse, a housing estate in close proximity to Rotterdam with no job opportunities of its own, which is not even worth visiting, holds a special record.
This municipality of 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To solve this stupid situation, a few years ago the decision was taken to contribute to universal education and to build seven nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures of the fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes.
But the success of the educational offensive was not dizzying.
And so the city councillors realized that there was only one way to become masters of statistics: we had to have a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural studio MVRDV, a master of insanely bold bar charts and a maker of witty, often cynical buildings, accepted the matter with the usual calm and appeared at the 2003 competition with five books under his arm and a smirk on his face.
And while the commission was still looking around in amazement and shrugging its shoulders, the cheeky Maas piled his presents on top of each other according to size and ended his activist-reasoned speech with the words, "Dear city community!"
So this is my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was piled up for 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Mountain of Books was awarded the second place "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
The grey small-town landscape, which has so far had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an unusually ugly town hall, behind whose white façade you would expect a dairy, is thus richer with a bit of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
A long way to the book
First impression: a reader's Eldorado under a cheese cover.
Although there is an elevator through the middle of the mountain massif, you will discover the real spatial and reading passions only when hiking the topography.
The glazed interior is bright and clear on all sides, the burnt cabron floor and elegant street lanterns clearly express the atmosphere of a public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, a dog and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books, books.
"Normally, there are bookshelves along the façade and in the middle is a big dark space that is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic spatial configuration upside down and pushed the reader's space from the inside out.
The interior of the Book Mountain is cleverly used: in the middle there are offices, an internet library, a chess club, an environmental centre and a switchboard.
A special pleasure is the black shelves for books, which are sometimes wall paneling, once parapet, and sometimes stair railings.
The appearance, texture and smell feel foreign.
Even sworn architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," says Joop Trouborst, project manager at Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard magazine.
And so, one day, in a Frisian farm, we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years, millimetre fleece made of synthetic material has been used as a substrate under the roots in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It is inexpensive and time efficient.
Thin textiles last for one or two seasons and then are ripe for disposal in bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in such quantities - was pressed into plates four centimeters thick.
Under the action of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous and loadable material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you reach the top.
At the end of the almost 500-metre-long journey, you will be rewarded in the literary café not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
They take care of the atmosphere, but mainly of the correct humidity in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for the New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite its many glass surfaces, this house is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled by the earth's heat.
Although the Mountain of Books stands under a glass hatch, the sun shines in only briefly, even on sunny days.
Wide glued wooden trusses, which stand perpendicular to the glazed façade, serve as shading and capture a large part of the sunlight.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
Fully automatic roller shutters can handle the rest.
Stefan Spermon, an initial skeptic in the IT industry, has already visited the new library.
Even Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde, who even refers to Boekenberg as the "long-awaited soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason: every resident of the city was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate a book from their personal collection.
First, the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library, which currently numbers 70,000 pieces, were to be filled.
The concept has proven successful.
The shelves are completely filled.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with the new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it was just for decoration.
In this way, MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which in professional jargon is called identity formation.
Spijkenisse wrote the history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated it is.
This is ultimately the starting point for identity.
Szabo: 'Germans must play a bigger role'
Germany abstained in deciding on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-Europe relations, Berlin is teetering on the narrow edge of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: Germany first signaled earlier this week that it would vote against the proposal for observer status for Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think they will support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained on the issue of establishing a no-fly zone.
This was eventually pushed through by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on serious international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason is that it is in the process of changing its foreign policy, away from a policy that was, so to speak, controlled by the US, towards German foreign policy.
The situation is made all the more difficult by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans are between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still settling into their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
To the foreign policy they have in France or Great Britain.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It shows readiness to adopt positions in the case of national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of other great powers, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to frighten the public, but also the elites in the Arab countries.
In any case, this plays a role.
But I wouldn't want to attach too much importance to it, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
In any case, it plays an important role in German considerations.
Did Germany's relations with the US suffer from abstaining on both important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe and even in the USA there is a great understanding for the German position.
Therefore, I do not think that it was such a dramatic turning point as on the issue of Libya.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect from this.
This signals that it must be regarded as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly spoken out in favor of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of American domestic politics.
I think that the Obama administration probably secretly has a great deal of sympathy for the European position.
But, of course, as a result of the political situation there, he cannot hold this position publicly.
I think that the differences of opinion are really not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US, on the one hand, and with the position of the EU's most important partners, on the other?
I think that is exactly what makes it difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not happening at present.
So they cannot be part of a broader line and must instead drive things forward from their own position.
That is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take a leading role in the future and push Europe towards a European position.
This, of course, is not easy for Germany, if only because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player? Does he even want to take the lead role?
Or is leadership still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable, and it is still difficult for this country to play a major role for obvious reasons.
For example, if we look at the European crisis, every time Germany takes on a bigger role, anti-German sentiment arises.
This does not make it easy for the Germans.
It's actually an old problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It has to be acceptable to all sorts of neighbours and opinions, and that is not easy.
US influence in European politics is now steadily declining, but the EU is not currently filling this vacuum. Who else is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it makes them uncomfortable and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America study together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani are suddenly Chinese
