Facts About Sexually Transmitted Infections
Which are the most serious sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Moths and scabies belong to parasitic SPI.
Who belongs to the group most affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur primarily in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five of all syphilis cases reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
In heterosexual adults, sexually transmitted diseases that occur frequently are chlamydial infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (mold), gonorrhea and human papillomaviruses.
HIV is relatively low among heterosexual adults in our country, but about 20 percent of those newly infected with HIV are in this group.
Among juveniles, chlamydial infections occur significantly more often than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In addition, human papillomaviruses are often found among juveniles in our country.
How did the number of infections develop?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases need to be reported.
The number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 in 2001 to 3698 in 2011, according to the Robert Koch Institute.
The number of people newly infected with HIV has been decreasing since 2007.
In 2011 there were about 2700 cases.
This is about one-tenth less than the year before.
What symptoms warn of a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause genital ulcers, difficulty urinating, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen and blisters or warts.
However, they often do not cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore go unnoticed.
How can I protect myself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they don't offer one hundred percent protection.
Because the causative agents of sexually transmitted diseases can also be partially transmitted by infection from impurities and close physical contact.
