Norwegian rakfisk: The smelliest fish in the world?
Five million people living in Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living not only in Europe but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be linked to the local appetite for an extraordinarily smelly fish?
Take a few overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty and wet football gear.
Let it lie for a week.
This gives you a sense of smell that paralyzes rakfisk, one of Norway's greatest delicacies.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow, a magnificent view - and a pervasive smell hangs in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout fermented in water for up to a year - it depends on how much you want the fish to smell.
As it gets dark and cold, Norwegians begin to gather here in Fagernes for a festival dedicated to this, how to put it best, the most captivating food.
"You eat it raw and then drink it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, a local professional firefighter who is also the so-called "Rakfisk General" who is responsible for the festival.
All around us, people eat small cubes of fish and wash them down with large amounts of alcohol.
"Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk," says Havard.
The drink can overwhelm the smell.
I'll try a few pieces.
If the fish can avoid your nose, it's not so bad - it's similar to a piece of sushi that was on a long bus journey.
Rakfisk is a product of a very different time when there was poverty in Norway, and because there were no refrigerators yet, the fish were soaked in airtight barrels of water and salt in autumn.
Then, in the middle of winter, when well fermented, they were pulled out and eaten—no doubt the senses were dulled by alcohol.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, most of whom emigrated to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants attracted by large amounts of work, high earnings and an extensive care system.
Residents of Sweden, an old rival that not long ago was much richer than Norway, flock to the country in search of work.
Rakfisk is seen as something important, an indispensable, if rather stinky, part of Norway's past.
It is one of the more expensive dishes on the market.
Although expensive is everything – a small glass of beer or a sandwich will set you back £9 ($14) apiece.
Norway does not often make it into the global news - and it seems that most of the population is happy with that.
The name of Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist extremist who shot dead 77 men, women and children last year, is still mentioned grudgingly.
Instead, the shooting is called the "July 22 event."
Norwegians can hardly believe that in their peaceful country one of them was capable of such brutality and murder.
Behind the current wealth of Norway lies the growth of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries in the early 70s of the twentieth century.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says our waitress Anna, who with her long blonde hair and surprisingly blue eyes is the prototype of Nordic prosperity as she serves plates of aged rakfisk.
We are, as you say, prudent people.
Her English, like the English of most people here, is impeccable.
We don't show off, we don't like pomp.
Norway is handling its oil wealth very carefully - except for a small percentage, most of the money from this sector is invested in a special fund intended for future generations.
When everyone else was throwing money they didn't have in the years leading up to the global financial crash, the Norwegians had the strings tightened on their purse.
"As long as we can ski in the winter and go on trips in the summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm standing in line in the snow for something to eat - I've had enough of rakfisk.
Such a moose burger is definitely something else and is beautifully juicy.
But in the evening the smelly fish is here again.
The hotel where I stay is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where guests vote for the best, or rather the most demanding fish to smell.
They have a connection to a live TV broadcast in which the presenter is with a bow tie surrounded by plates of rakfisk.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thore-Juergen?"
"Here's our scoring, Havard."
There is applause and laughter.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps overwhelmed by aquavit.
Or maybe the fumes from all those fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto gets off to a tough start
As incoming Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office, the BBC's Will Grant looks at the challenges he faces and the mixed expectations of his fellow citizens.
Traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city clogged even in the best of times, steel barriers have been erected, closing several key routes into the capital and wreaking havoc on the roads.
The aim was not to prevent commuters from getting to work, but to prevent protesters from accessing parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential sash and take over the leadership of the nation.
They face a daunting task.
Mexico has done well economically under outgoing Felipe Calderon, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already claimed an estimated 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government has a great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence," President Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before shaking hands with the US president, President Pena Nieta gained political experience as governor of his home state of Mexico.
Opinions about the new leader are divided even in his old homeland, a populous and sprawling state surrounding the capital.
Straight man.
For example, in the rural town of Valle del Bravo, he is remembered in a good way.
Citizens attribute to him the development of tourism in the resort and the construction of infrastructure.
You can now reach the city via one of the new motorways built by Pena Nieto. These highways are a huge improvement over the leaky and bumpy roads that used to be here.
Plaques with his name also hang on the wall of a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect it to bring real and lasting change," says friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state MP for President Pena Nieto's party, the Party of Institutionalized Revolution (PRI).
In particular, we hope for interesting and real changes in the security and economy that our country so badly needs.
After an uninterrupted 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted by Vicente Fox.
MP Olvera admits that after 12 years away from the presidential palace of Los Pinos, much is expected of Enrique Pena Nieto within the party.
And he rejects the opposition's statements characterizing the new president as a man without substantial content.
He is a very straightforward person, very interested with an excellent vision of the country.
He is a great statesman and, above all, he is a man who knows how to listen.
But on the other side of the state, this is not the impression that many people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be more obvious.
Tucked under highway overpasses, it resembles the suburbs of the Mexican capital itself.
And the problems in the self-governing municipality are also persistent and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called in to help control drug gangs operating in neighborhoods, particularly acute violence against women.
In the last two years alone, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been dumped in desolate places next to a huge garbage dump.
During Pena Nieto's time as governor, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico, far more than in the notoriously violent city of Ciudad Juarez — a place synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
At best, Pena Nieto's critics say that during his time in office, he failed to adequately address the problem of feminicide.
Worse, they accuse his leadership of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of a dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendia shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna and suppresses her tears.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner murdered her.
"When I arrived at her house, it looked like her body had been washed," recalls Ms. Buendia.
There were marks of blows on him, and the postmortem stiffness had already begun.
As her mother tells the story, Mariana looks down from the picture on the wall, right next to the cross, which has a single word on it: "Justice."
However, this, the family says, is exactly what they were denied.
The authorities treated me like I was an old gossip, a troublemaker, and a whiner.
They want you to just accept what they say and keep quiet.
"But that can't be right when there have been so many mistakes and omissions," he says.
The sash that President Pena Nieto will receive on Saturday is accompanied by great responsibility.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been hit by violent crime, and the new president has vowed to make them a priority for his tenure.
"I hope he will be the same president as he was governor," said PRI MP Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But this is exactly what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, military prosecutor says
The military prosecutor is trying to refute Bradley Manning's allegations of abuse in custody.
The hearing focuses on Manning's time in military custody in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants the case dismissed based on Manning's abuse in prison.
A soldier is accused of stealing thousands of secret documents.
A military prosecutor is trying to prove that Private Bradley Manning, who is accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, missed many opportunities to complain about the abuse he allegedly suffered in military custody.
Military Attorney Maj. Ashden Fein, in cross-examining Private Manning at a preliminary hearing at Ft. Maede, Maryland, claimed that records of weekly visits Manning had with unit officers during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, showed no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination, which took place during a hearing conducted at the defense request to dismiss the case against Manning for abuse while in custody, which is a sufficient sentence in itself, took place the day after Manning testified that he had contemplated suicide while in custody.
An army intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents while serving in Iraq.
The material was then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of its information.
At Friday's hearing, Defense Attorney Fein and Manning went through the forms officers filled out after meeting Manning at Quantico Detention Center, where he was held in a high-security regime from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the overall treatment at the facility as "very professional."
The forms show no complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly asked Manning about how he was being treated, Fein claimed.
Manning replied that he had expressed concerns about various problems verbally, and that officers who visited him had spoken to him about these concerns and indicated that they would address them, but did not notice these problems.
"They wrote down 'no problems' (after discussing concerns), and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't mention them," Manning said.
Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment in January 2011 during a meeting with a commission assessing suicidal thoughts that he had expressed in a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during this meeting his intention was to achieve a reduction in the "injury prevention" regime.
The military said it used this restrictive regime (one level below the suicide surveillance regime) for his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the guards in custody to know that I was fine and that I wanted to lift this injury prevention regime... so that I can enjoy the increased quality of life that I have seen," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transported to a detention center at Marine Corps Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once fainted because of the heat.
He said that not being allowed to know what would happen to him and what was happening in the outside world was very disheartening.
"My world has shrunk to the Arifjan base, to that cage," Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Manning said that after arriving in Quantico, he spent most days (at least 21 hours, but often longer than 23 hours) in a small cell with no company.
Manning said he was only allowed one mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and glasses.
He said he tried to walk because sleeping or just lying down was against regulations during the day.
Manning said he always slept with light from outside the cell in his eyes.
He stated that if the guards could not see his face when he turned to the other side at night, they woke him up and he had to turn back.
Manning's attorney filed a formal complaint about Private Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was transferred to a military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge also questioned Manning about the allegations he made in Thursday's testimony that after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night, he was also forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates during the morning count.
Manning testified that he was not allowed to cover himself with his blanket while counting.
Under questioning by the judge on Friday, Manning said he had decided from his guards' orders to put down the blanket he could cover, but admitted that no one had given him an order to put it away.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because he had tried to show an officer that he was not dangerous.
Manning said he told the officer that he could use his underwear belt or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but he didn't.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyer hopes the judge will take into account his experience during his imprisonment and significantly reduce his sentence if he is convicted before a military court, which is expected to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to see Manning plead guilty to lower offenses and fight the other charges because they are too extreme.
With hearings scheduled to begin this week, the military prosecutor is expected to defend the detention conditions as justified.
The Pentagon said in a statement that Manning was being held in accordance with regulations governing all arrestees held in maximum security custody.
The charges against Manning include aiding an enemy, illegally causing intelligence documents to be published online, transmitting national security information, and stealing public property or records.
If convicted on all counts, he could be sentenced to life in prison.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He says many people have been forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of options there are.
Mexicans tend to blame those who have left; They remind them of hard times, he says.
Navarrette says Mexican Americans are caught between two worlds.
On my last trip to Mexico City, I barely made it through the crowd and arrived at the Immigrant Agenda Area where I ran into a problem.
The arrows pointed to one of two fronts: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans") and the other for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California and have been called "Mexican" all my life.
It's an ethnic acronym, just like when my friends in Boston call themselves "Irish" and my friends in New York call themselves "Italians."
So later I ended up with the label "Mexican American."
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's homeland, it was not necessary to use abbreviations.
I was simply an American.
I speak Spanish, good enough to handle both sides of a conversation in that language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker and I can't get rid of the American accent.
So I pulled out my American passport and lined up for "Extranjeros".
I thought about the moment this week when Mexico's president-elect, Enrique Pena Nieto, visited President Obama at the White House.
On the agenda were the usual issues that are discussed when the leaders of the two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto also wanted to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons why Mexicans are just as likely to stay in Mexico as they are to travel to the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada to create a trading bloc in North America similar to the European Union.
And Pena Nieto has vowed to continue Mexico's war against drug cartels, though he has not provided any details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and fraught with hostility.
Most Americans probably never thought of the fact that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to transfer half of Mexican territory to the United States under threat of arms.
But for Mexicans who think in terms of centuries, not minutes, reminders are ubiquitous.
So a minute after a U.S. official says something even slightly critical about Mexico, you will hear complaints in the Mexican press and among the elite about the Americans encroaching on their neighbor's sovereignty.
And Montezuma's children step out onto the warpath.
And yet the real challenge for Mexico is its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Do you want to talk about hostile feelings?
There are a lot of those.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people to whom the country offers opportunities and others to whom it does not.
The only reason so many people with Mexican roots live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at some point in our family tree there was a person, maybe a parent or grandparent, who was denied an opportunity in Mexico and had to go north.
And more often than it would seem, this person matched the profile - dark skin, weak education, origin from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not to Mexico.
And even though we are now living the American dream, going to good schools, and having good jobs, we can never forget the fact that we are living the American dream, not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be unclear, but our loyalty is not.
It is against the United States.
And besides, we are aware that many elite Mexicans belonging to the ruling class do not like us.
This feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and see us as an inferior race that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
Our existence, in their view, is all about failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would never have left.
And we would not find ourselves now trapped behind the Silk Curtain, with a good life in the United States, but still with lost souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and traveled legally to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is tension between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because Mexicans understand more about who they are, and Mexican Americans resent it.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she sees herself as part of two countries.
At the same time, many Mexican Americans I know don't feel like part of either.
We love listening to Mexican bands, Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You get the best of both countries, but you don't have roots in either.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
And to complicate relations further, some Mexican leaders and some of the intelligentsia, as I learned during my trip, want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican Americans to work for Mexico as "makeshift ambassadors" and represent Mexican interests in the United States.
We should be telling our fellow Americans how wonderful it is to visit this country and putting pressure on political leaders to strengthen relations with Mexico.
Well.
So that is not going to happen.
Too many hostile feelings.
And with income inequality and widespread corruption and drug violence, many of us aren't sure it's a great country.
I have a feeling it's up to you, amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not prepared to forgive the United States for how it treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must accept that some Mexican Americans still resentment at the way their family members were treated in the much closer past.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
A ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could still be an uncertain basis for peace.
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed suggests that any such failure is futile.
Among the usual futile guesses about who started it, many buildings were reduced to rubble, killing more than 140 Palestinians, mostly civilians, and six Israelis. And for the first time, rockets from Gaza landed near Tel Aviv, the Israeli capital, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even when Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their ancient conflict, the Middle East is changing all around them.
The Arab Spring has changed the old order, and Palestinians and Israelis, whether they like it or not, are caught up in the ensuing chaos in the region.
Perhaps this will make their fight bloodier than ever.
However, there are reasons to think that this may break their deadly stalemate.
A war that is neither won nor lost.
At first glance, there seems to be little reason for optimism at the moment.
Even if the November 21 ceasefire holds, this week's fighting has strengthened hawks on both sides.
Leaders of Hamas, the Islamic movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to retreat, even though Gaza has suffered a defeat.
Despite the killing of several Hamas leaders and the closure of 1.7 million Gazans in one of the most deplorable and populous corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining influence in the West Bank, another piece of Palestine currently controlled by its bitter rivals in Fatah, the more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is on their side.
Islamists have gained more influence throughout the Arab world, so Hamas has gained powerful and wealthy friends.
Turkey, a resurrected regional power that was once Israel's closest Muslim ally, has sided with Hamas. So is Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic countries in the Gulf.
Cheering Hamas people say the Islamic Crescent wraps around Israel, in the north from Lebanon, ruled by the Hezbollah party/militia, through Syria, where increasingly Islamic-leaning rebels may topple Bashar al-Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
Above all, on Israel's southern flank, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Mohamed Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and pivotal Arab country, has changed the balance in the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had no time for Hamas.
The Brotherhood, on the other hand, is a cousin of Hamas and its leaders are more susceptible to public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas may emerge as a player that cannot be excluded by either Israel or America.
Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, will come to the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas was put back in a box.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system proved its worth, and many Hamas rockets were destroyed.
Israelis can sleep better - for a while.
In diplomatic terms, America is as steadfast as ever. Many European countries also blamed Hamas for launching the latest round of violence.
Most importantly, Israel prospered, especially under the leadership of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from Gaza have killed some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been relatively calm from suicide bombers, thanks in part to a wall that encroaches on the West Bank, a major part of what may one day be a Palestinian state, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to grow despite their illegality from international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party allied itself with an even more radical group led by Avigdor Lieberman at the start of the January 22 election campaign, is in a good position.
Why spoil those treacherous Palestinians by giving them their own state?
If they really ruled the West Bank, wouldn't they fire rockets like their compatriots did in Gaza?
We'd better keep them behind that wall and punch them when they stick their heads out.
Hardliners may win, but the Arab Spring may change their calculations.
Even if the Islamists gaining power in Egypt and other countries have little love for Israel, their top priority will be to deal with domestic problems.
Israel's defense spending is higher than that of all four of its Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a new war with a local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to heal their economies.
That President Morsi worked with President Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire is a good sign and may mark the beginning of something new.
Israelis, too, should look at the situation in the long term.
At a time when the rest of the Arab world is becoming more democratic, denying Palestinians the right to self-determination is creating a powder keg that must one day explode in Israeli-occupied areas - just like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv last week.
Repression is already weakening democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics are making the situation worse as the Arab population grows.
The bloody incursions against Gaza every few years to push back Hamas will increasingly take a diplomatic toll.
Both sides need incentives from outside.
The answer is what reasonable people on both sides are saying, most of the outside world and this newspaper: two states where Israel cedes territory for security.
In the short term, there is some hope that a ceasefire will give outside pressure at least a little more influence to enforce the cause.
Egypt, which, together with Turkey and Qatar, must work to stop arms shipments to Gaza, is in a better position than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with parts of the country swapped and a shared Jerusalem.
Outsiders also need to push for agreement between Hamas and Fatah.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than an immediate offer of virtual state sovereignty at the UN.
President Obama also has his share of getting Israel to the negotiating table.
In his first term, he neglected to present his own peace plan.
Now, back in the White House, he seems equally reluctant in his entry into the process.
This is woefully short-sighted.
America has a vital interest in a stable Middle East.
This means a peace settlement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Ugly cigarette packaging laws come into force in Australia
On the unsightly green boxes, which are the same for all brands of tobacco, warnings for smokers and diseased body parts are depicted.
Australia's ugly tobacco and cigarette packaging laws, the first of its kind in the world, came into force, replacing logos and brand colours with generic olive-green boxes with hideous pictures of diseased body parts and images of children and newborns sick as a result of their parents' smoking.
Apart from various health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the boxes from Saturday are the names of the brands, which are printed in the same small print.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
Australia's federal government says the aim is to discourage young people from smoking by depriving the habit of its appeal.
It relies on studies that show that if people don't start smoking by the age of 26, there's a 99% chance they will never start smoking.
"Even with very young children, you can see that they understand the message that the tobacco companies are trying to sell them along with their product," says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown in the logo with the idea of being a princess.
While Australia has one of the lowest numbers of smokers in the world and the changes will have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are considering similar steps.
The tobacco industry lobbied hard against the introduction of these laws.
The tobacco companies claimed that the law would increase black market trading, leading to cheaper and more affordable cigarettes.
"There will be serious unintended consequences with this legislation," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring many more of these products to sell on Australian streets.
Another claims that the laws have increased their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said demand for silicone cigarette packaging used to cover disgusting packs had increased from almost zero sales two months ago when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost their appeal over the laws to the Supreme Court of Australia.
Ha said Zico has sold nearly 6,000 units to wholesalers and expects new inventory.
It's a good deal for us.
As a possible hitch, experts cite the popularity of social media among the demographic targeted by the plan.
Following a series of Australian laws banning TV advertising, sponsorship of sporting events and requiring most retailers to hide cigarettes from direct view, tobacco marketing has moved online.
Australia has banned internet advertising by local companies and websites, but cannot restrict foreign sites.
"If you're a marketer in the tobacco industry and all you have left is this little space to promote your products, the online space is an unbeatable place for you to be in," says Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Ms. Freeman noted an increase in the ratings of brands on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook conducted by the "average John".
We have to ask, is this just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and took the trouble to create this video, or is a marketing company involved?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry has focused on how it will deal with the new regulations rather than marketing.
The industry has gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations - countries within the World Trade Organisation claim that trade is unfairly restricted, despite the fact that none of the countries trade significantly with Australia.
The CPC decision is expected in mid-2013.
Minister Plibersek says the government has held talks with other governments considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to introduce mandatory warning photos in 2001.
They have now spread to more than 40 countries including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India are considering stricter laws.
Many smokers in Australia resist.
Pictures have no effect on me.
I just ignore them.
"You just pull out a cigarette and put it back," says Victor El Hage, buying a box with a photo of a tumor in his mouth.
Honestly, there is only one reason for me to quit smoking, and that is my little daughter.
James Yu, who owns King of the Pack newsagents in central Sydney, says the uniform boxes make it harder for him to stack them.
"It took me one hour to unload the cargo, now it takes me four hours," Yu said.
"The government should just ban them completely, then we'd say, 'OK, that's it, let's close the shop,'" he said, throwing up his hands.
In a world of constant connection, it's not so bad to be bored
