But says Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada who is the author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011).
"In fact, boredom has a long history," he said.
On the walls in Pompeii was found a Latin inscription concerning boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there is also the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After viewing the research literature and presenting the idea to a target audience of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience of "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I was unable to do it".
Boredom is distinguished from apathy by the fact that the person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says that with apathy, there is no urge to do something.
He says that at the heart of boredom is "the disruption of the attention process associated with a bad mood and a sense of time slowly passing."
Boredom can be very reminiscent of depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a relationship with each other, bored people tend to see the problem as an environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored when we just have trouble concentrating.
In their study, "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which a person read a journal article.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while a third group did not hear it at all.
Those who heard the TV program quietly reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, but weren't sure why, and attributed the trouble to boredom.
When you try to focus on a difficult or engaging task, distracted attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, "like finding the wrong parts on the factory line, distracting music can help keep you from getting bored."
In fact, he said, we now know that twisting and doodling, which is often seen as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat boredom and keep people more physically attentive.
"Research shows that children who are allowed to fidget learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," Professor Fenske said.
We've all experienced boredom at some point - my flight delay, a roaring speaker, a particularly lengthy movie.
But some individuals are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure boredom, scientists developed the "Boredom Proneness Scale" in the 80s.
The scale includes questions like, "Many things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all."
Using these scales, researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimulations.
However, teenagers are generally indifferent.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored at school and doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they weren't at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the percentage of boredom would be higher or lower now, 21 years later.
But he said he knows that "adolescence is the peak time for boredom," which is largely due to the fact that children and teens aren't given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question: "Is boredom good for you?".
As research shows, sometimes not, because in its extreme form it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, gamble or abuse addictive substances as a way to mitigate it.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have discussed the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
"Boredom is the brain's way of telling you that you should be doing something else," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn't always know the most appropriate thing to do.
If you are bored and use this energy to play the guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a while, not in the long run.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he won't be bored anymore, but he won't learn how to entertain himself or drive himself, Professor Fenske said.
And "this self-management is transferred from one situation to another," the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain himself, but will gain more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we should not be too critical of it either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable when we are away from the constant rattle of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agreed.
"We blame her for needing to be bored even more, but boredom is a painful, restless desire to be connected to something meaningful," he said.
What people are actually looking for, he said, is a way to relax and enjoy their free time.
"In an environment where we're constantly overstimulated," he said, "it's hard to find ways to entertain ourselves when the noise goes off."
There is no manual in Colorado regarding the new marijuana law
Nineteen-year-old Anthony Orozco, a college student and soccer player from southeastern Colorado, faces criminal charges for something that will soon become legal across the state — possession of several grams of marijuana and a pipe he used to smoke it.
Mr. Orozco said he was riding with some friends in Lamar, on the plains near the Kansas border, one day in September when he was stopped.
After a police officer found marijuana in his car, Mr. Orozco was issued a subpoena for possession of drugs and drug paraphernalia — minor offenses punishable by $100 each fine — and set a trial date.
"They treated us like criminals," Mr. Orozco said.
But is he a criminal?
In the uncertain weeks following Colorado's vote to legalize small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the response to hundreds of smaller drug cases depends on location rather than law.
Hundreds of marijuana misdemeanors have already been dropped here and in Washington state, which has passed similar measures.
The police department has stopped charging adults aged 21 and older for possession of small amounts that will be legally permitted after the law goes into effect in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado's more conservative districts have said they will continue with existing marijuana cases and are still charging people for possession.
At the same time, several cities in suburban Denver toward the western mountains are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
"This issue is evolving so fast that I don't know what's going to happen next," said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
Even regulators in Washington state are scratching their heads.
And they are looking for guidance on how to set up a licensing system for cultivation, production, distribution and sale - all by the December 1, 2013 deadline.
They say Colorado, for better or worse, leads most states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use and now for recreational use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide," said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Licensing Board.
But as Mr. Smith admitted, no place or system can do more than suggest what might work.
"There is no real precedent to follow," he said.
The Washington Act, the so-called Washington Act. I-502, takes effect on December 6, also leaving a year-long vacuum during which there will not yet be a state licensing system, but legal possession will.
And there are tricky mechanical issues that must be resolved during this time, such as how to balance the state's "appropriate access" directive to licensed marijuana with its ban on cannabis trade within 330 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds or children's centers.
"Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis store than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area," said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently established research group.
On November 21, Aurora Police Chief Oates sent an email to his officers telling them that the city prosecutor would no longer prosecute misdemeanors for possession of small amounts of marijuana for any citizen over the age of 21, and that police would stop charging people for these crimes "effective immediately."
Chief Oates said police would enforce city laws regulating medical marijuana growers and that they would continue to prosecute drug traffickers and dealers.
In Weld County, northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck takes a tougher view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mostly as a way to pressure users to seek treatment.
Currently, 119 people face charges of possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many face additional charges.
"Our office has a duty to prosecute criminal offences that were crimes at the time they were committed," Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The response was complicated even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected a marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county's largest town, no longer charge adults with possession of small amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supports the decision, but has also decided not to dismiss all ongoing detention cases.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time continuing to enforce the law until it changes," he said.
Although 55 percent of Colorado voters supported the measure, bringing recreational marijuana into the arms of the government and the legal system will never be easy.
And the conflicting reactions across the state have exposed deep divisions among local officials in the face of this great state green experiment.
It's a "cultural barrier" for district attorneys, said Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney representing marijuana possession defendants and a local spokesman for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
"They've spent so much of their lives prosecuting people that they still can't really accept it's legal," he said.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are on track to become national test cases for legalizing the drug.
Advocates and state authorities are planning new frontiers for legalized sales, while also anxiously awaiting guidance from the federal government, which still plans to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Advocates of marijuana legalization hope the Justice Department will comply.
Despite several arrests of medical marijuana sellers and patients who use it that have attracted attention, the federal government has mostly kept medical marijuana stores in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states operating.
While drug agents probably won't break down doors to grab a small bag of drugs, they're likely to resist allowing state-regulated recreational marijuana stores allowed under new laws, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser in the Obama administration.
Several Colorado cities are not waiting for federal authorities to advance.
Even before Election Day, some local governments had approved moratoriums on any new marijuana stores, though it will be about a year before any store can open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose proposed a six-month ban and is likely to go into effect next week.
"We don't want to find ourselves in a situation where we give someone a license and then we make it a big federal issue," said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We look at what the municipality voted for versus what the state voted for.
There are really many questions.
Petronella Wyatt: "I was forced to leave Oxford because I'm a Conservative."
It's not just today's university students who are being attacked for their opinions.
I don't remember ever dreaming of studying at the University of Oxford.
Both my father and my older brother studied at a university that I thought was the world's largest seat of knowledge, a modern wrapped Greek symposium motivating the two pillars of civilization, free thought and tolerance.
Meanwhile, in the late 80s of the twentieth century, within two weeks of entering Worcester College, where I wanted to study history, I packed my bags and plunged into the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I had given up because I objected to the students making love in the next room.
The writer A. N. Wilson cheerfully declared that I left because I was forced to drink from battered mugs.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was subject to systematic bullying and intimidation.
Not because of my rather bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for one reason, and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment, it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a senior adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
You may ask why I'm bringing it up now.
Simply because recent reports suggest that a new generation of right-of-center students are suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalised and growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week a group of them demanded the same protection of equal rights as gays, people with disabilities and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Younger Generation Association (JCR) at Corpus Christi College say they are "often actively isolated, subjected to personal attacks, and told they are not welcome because of their political views."
They call for the creation of a position on the university's equal opportunities committee to ensure that they can freely express their views.
Their situation was not helped by a recent BBC Two documentary about student politics, which portrayed conservatives as weirdos and neo-Nazis.
The programme featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), who drove a Rolls-Royce, was dressed in a silver suit and wore a silver-headed cane.
At other colleges, conservative students say they are being treated as "scapegoats" because of the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Twenty-year-old Luke Black, vice-president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told a Sunday newspaper that "left-wing influence in universities is growing.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even meeting us."
Twenty-one-year-old Corpus Christi history student Samuel Roberts, who is behind the More Protection Movement, says the climate is "uncomfortable," while nineteen-year-old OUCA president-elect Stephanie Cherill says there has been a deterioration in JCR members' attitude toward right-of-center people.
"This poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion, as well as to the well-being of members," he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford, I was a minority of one member.
I joined in September 1986, 18 years old and crippling shy.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was most feverish.
A year earlier, the university had voted to deny the award of an honorary degree to former student Margaret Thatcher because of cuts in funding for higher education.
The atmosphere would make even the Stalinists tremble with fear.
During the first few days of the introductory week, when the new students socialize with each other and with the professors, I got a taste of wormwood that was to come.
I have found that not only do professors tacitly approve of the teasing of conservative students, but they also enjoy participating in it.
A policy of miners' strike, privatisation and government resistance to sanctions against apartheid in South Africa was brought into the wood-panelled lecture halls.
My first lecture was about translating an 18th-century French text into English, and I wasn't prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
It was pretty tough for me.
Professor Pitt, a small man with a face like cake dough, was very bile-like.
"Do the Thatcherites refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked.
The other students giggled.
Tears welled up in my eyes.
"I suggest you take some basic French lessons in your spare time, unless you're too busy with social affairs," Professor Pitt growled.
Devastated, I returned to my room.
I was sitting alone at dinner at school when I felt a light tap on the shoulder.
It was a second-year student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, this is so.
Anyone suspected of conservatism is a target.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be even worse for you.
Most Conservative freshmen pretend to be Labour.
Later, in the local pub, I cowardly tried to pretend.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Thatcher said.
This trick turned out to be unsuccessful.
A first-year student in philosophy, politics and economics who (ironically) attended Eton, said, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're infected.
The other students took notes with him.
I was perverted, dirty.
"How do conservatives love each other?" asked one.
They beat each other, don't they?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the liberal legislation of the sixties.
Could I ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Would I have to change into Labour and suppress my natural inclinations?
Three years unfolded before me as purgatory of ignorance and isolation.
The only openly conservative professor was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history who was based on my faculty.
He was hated not only for being conservative, but also for being Margaret Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of those who wrote her speeches.
He was almost not there.
He hated the place for its parochialism and pettiness, and for its adherence to a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he became a professor at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began commuting from Oxford to my parents' house in London, seeking refuge with my disinterested metropolitan friends and family.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why.
He couldn't believe it.
During his studies at Oxford in the forties, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said pathetically.
They wouldn't do that, not in a city of dreamy moods.
Even my communist friends always had perfect manners.
His moist eyes grimaced.
Try again.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by frequent trips to London, my emotional resilience deteriorated.
My friend, also a Conservative Party supporter, succumbed to pressure and gave up his convictions.
The following week, during class, when another history professor declared in all seriousness that I was an "enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Even though I was blushing with shame inside, I admitted that "my parents had brainwashed me" and called them "old fools."
The relief was short-lived.
The nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was driven by my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns a week for Murdoch's newspaper.
My door was locked.
I crouched inside, and after five minutes my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and caught the first train to London.
I never went back.
You can call me a smirking weakling.
But no 18-year-old girl or boy should be subjected to such intimidation and poison in an educational institution.
Even more tragically, it was Oxford that not only produced 14 Conservative prime ministers, but which to this day hides behind an undeserved reputation as a place of equality and freedom of thought.
