The toughest craft in the world: sulfur carriers in the area of the Kawah Ijen volcano
For four euros, porters in the Indonesian volcano area gamble with their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur down steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
Such is the case of Ant Wijayi, one of 400 miners who earn their living extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, it has to go to the bottom of the crater every day, where sulfur gases escape from the interior of the Earth and go into a solid state upon contact with air.
After cutting large blocks of sulphur, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises 2,386 meters, but it takes over 40 minutes for exhausted porters to climb up at turtle pace, as they keep their balance and carefully consider their steps so as not to slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any stumble could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell from the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
When they are at the top, they make their way past tourists, who photograph them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and wearily carry heavy baskets to a vase that the mining company has placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 meters.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been mining in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
It takes him three hours to make one trip and he is devastated at the end, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (€11.5) per day.
While this seems like a negligible sum for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the field.
"The daily wages of miners here are very high. For example, collecting coffee costs 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the salary for a fortnight is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the porter, who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a bricklayer.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as compelling as sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a young girl from Bali who is Hindu, and I took her to Java,  to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, difficulty breathing, coughs all the time, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks his life three times a day in the Kawah Ijen volcano, whose sulphur has already begun to take its toll on him, even though his face is protected by a special mask and glasses.
He has asthma, difficulty breathing, coughs all the time, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases escaping from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll be working for another two years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than decent English.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man with fate could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, and instead does a porter job.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other porters and gets up at two o'clock in the morning every day, because the sulphur does not stop rising at night and its characteristic yellow colour turns blue and glows through the darkness.
Despite the surrounding darkness, Anto climbs into the crater and lights his way with a small torch attached to his helmet and bought with his own money.
About 400 carriers carry baskets of sulfur from the crater floor on their shoulders
Although the company has high incomes, it has not mechanized sulphur mining to save costs, nor does it provide any equipment to porters working on their own and with such effort.
In fact, they don't even get a share of the 30,000 rupees (€2.5) of the photography surcharge that, along with a 15,000 rupee (€1.2) ticket, is collected by nature rangers from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for cattle, not for people," said Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old porter who has worked in Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He can lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he can work "as long as he can" because he needs money for the education of his three sons, between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings in the eyes when the wind unexpectedly turns and traps the miners in the thick fumes that emanate from the volcano, the miners are so hard that none of them complain of suffering from serious illnesses... However, this is evident from their frequent respiratory problems, arthrosis, knee pain and shoulder wounds caused by the weight of the baskets.
Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, can only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his colleagues mine 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which are then transported by three trucks along a steep path between thickets to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometres away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik declares, opening his mouth wide, which is missing several teeth.
Of his five sons, the eldest, thirty, also earns his living by mining sulphur.
Time passes, but the constant misery of one of the most difficult crafts in the world persists from generation to generation - crafts performed by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save economy
Singaporeans blame not having children on careers, stress, and the cost of living and education.
"The population of Singapore needs to grow."
I am married and I am a patriot, you are my wife and you are a patriot. Let us fulfill our civic duty and beget new life!
