The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and allocates financial benefits.
But all these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and strict social controls.
Singapore's fertility rate with respect to population stratification is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the fertility rate exceeded 2, which is considered the recovery rate, was in 1976.
Why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Marriage and Family Department at the National Bureau of Population, says this is due to "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities."
"It gives people a wider range of options when it comes to life goals and priorities, not just marriage and family," he explains.
These changes in social norms contributed to an increase in the number of single people and to the postponement of marriage and childbreeding. The result is a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
While there were attempts to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure to counter population decline, this caused resentment among the local population.
Some Singaporean websites show undisguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and making little effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party last year recorded its worst election result since independence began.
After the elections, there was an effort to solve the problem through quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in the birth rate has had known effects on national economic growth, tax revenues, health spending, and immigration policies, Singapore has also had some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to influence the real estate business.
The Urban Development Authority has begun regulating the number of small apartments known as "shoeboxes" that can be built in certain urban zones.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have had great success in marketability.
However, there is concern that these apartments may encourage a bachelor lifestyle and discourage developers from building large single-family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of development firm EL Developers, says their "shoeboxes" sell much faster than larger homes.
"They are more popular in that they sell days or weeks faster than houses with a larger area.
Therefore, they are much better for our cash flow."
However, he admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers, who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
Although the new rules could be aimed at boosting the nation's birth rate, interviews with Singaporeans working in the downtown financial district suggest they won't have much effect.
"People are always stressed, houses are expensive, as is education, so many people put it off," says the young official.
"Let the others have children.
But for me it's important to rely on my own money and time," says another, about twenty years old.
Both men and women cite career, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons preventing them from having children.
So no matter how much the government tries to force people to have children, it is ultimately the Singaporeans who have the final say on starting a family.
What's private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to the vocabulary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something of a personal nature or "an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any interference".
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social media?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone in his normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15, who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered privacy to be "something entirely of one's own" on a personal level, and a "username and password" when it came to social networks.
"I wouldn't disclose my biggest secrets," says ten-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom can know about them, but not the whole world," she said.
"On FB I put nice photos or photos of us playing.
I also talk to friends there.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine or a photo that made someone laugh," he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to post obscene photos, nude photos or photographs of crimes, or to write demeaning or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and nine followers on Twitter.
Most are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I set up a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there," he adds.
"Social media is fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or communicate quickly with friends," he says.
He says without hesitation that he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The case of fourteen-year-old José is different.
The teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and admits he doesn't know 20 people on his friends list for the latter.
"I'm not worried about it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to the boy, none of them instructed him to do anything, nor did they ask him for an address or phone number.
"If they pressure me or require me to, I will simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José signed up for Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
This boy is no stranger to the experience of what is now called cyberbullying (cyberbullying).
"A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who it was," he confirms.
The victim did not log out of the account, according to José.
"She just activated private mode."
He then explains a series of steps on how to set up your account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post photos of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would do it if someone bothered me or I just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and graduate of Education and Teaching, believes that in order to navigate social networks, children and adolescents need to understand that the main goal of social networks is to inform.
He states that: "The Internet originated as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate student in education at Yale University and author of Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born in the age of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and we are just learning ourselves," he says.
He explains that it is a complex subject "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ripe for it."
Also to be - as far as the surroundings are concerned - sober, at a time when what they most want is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to show children and teens what privacy is is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Marrielos Porras lists some of the possibilities: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or: Would you like it if someone posted a picture of you the way you posted your friend's?
Do you know what others publish about you?
When you tag people in party photos, have you asked their permission?
And one more thing: Does everyone always need to know what you're doing?
Another point is for them to realize that they have to behave in the same way in the Internet environment as they do outside it.
They are the same rules.
"Outside of the internet, one is guided by respect, morality and other principles, and it should be the same on social media," he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and educational consultant, explains that it is essential for parents of children to carefully read the rules of social networks.
"If they understand every tricky thing, they have a good basis to talk to their children about the consequences of opening an account on the Internet.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to share or post," he says.
Guardia believes it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of "don't talk to strangers".
The South American summit ends and the Lima Declaration has not been published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru ended today without the Lima Declaration, which was announced and reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the sixth meeting of Unasur's heads of state and government, but representatives of both the Foreign Ministry and the President's Office, who initially stipulated that they would publish the document after the summit, said it would later be published on the Peruvian government's website.
They further stated that the content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several short press releases.
Journalists had restricted access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential rally without sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "confidential session, audio transmission blocked".
The small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the spokespersons of some governments who were present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the meeting was a list of participating presidents, which provoked outrage from hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets who demanded more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent an email to the media with a "final statement" from the summit, but this is only President Humala's statement and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of South American and Arab countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA), and even on this occasion the Lima Declaration originally promised was not published, despite being eagerly demanded by the press.
On the official ASPA website, it can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure that all journalists were broadcast, but completely shut down the flow of information.
The summit ended with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to accept the Hague Court of Justice ruling on the border dispute between the two countries.
Peru's President Ollanta Humala and Chilean President Sebastián Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they will respect the ruling of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin hearing the dispute opened by Lima against Santiago on Monday by hearing a defense speech from both sides.
"We will comply and execute a judgment that will resolve the dispute we are hearing today in this international court," President Humala said alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will be a country respecting international law, peaceful dispute resolution, conventions and international courts," Piñera added, greeting President Humala with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The two presidents' confirmation that they would comply with the ruling of the International Court of Justice was made public after Colombia adopted the Bogotá Pact this week, expressing its submission to the judgments of the international court that ruled on the maritime border with Nicaragua, a decision that Colombia considered completely wrong.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 following the dismissal of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening the morning speeches and closing the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The president read the final document, in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and work had been planned on 31 projects between South American countries, with investments of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR member countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which residence agreements are being extended."
He informed that actions are being supported to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil insecurity and international organized crime, to improve the availability of medicines and cheap Internet in all corners of South America, and to take joint and effective action against the risks of natural disasters."
When Europe is in crisis, "economic consolidation [of Latin America] should not have a winning essence, but serve to expand our productivity and show our nations a better future," Humala added.
"We decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport links between different places in South America, especially rural and border areas... so that our countries are better connected and create new economic ties," the Peruvian president said in a speech read.
He mentioned that five of these projects concern Peru and the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and the other two concern better connections with Ecuador, but did not give further details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return her to the Union of South American Nations", from which she is currently expelled.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region that is whole and has good neighbourly relations.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to respectfully discuss the judgment of the International Court of Justice concerning the maritime boundary dispute, which is disputed by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I will meet with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will discuss all solutions, none are ruled out, not even a treaty with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with that country," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega to conduct the negotiations in the most civilized and considerate form possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico to attend the inauguration of President Enrique Peña Nieto.
In the margins of the summit, EU defence ministers met provisionally to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
UNASUR members are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru is the interim president of this regional bloc.
Rafael Correa: South America must learn integration from Europe
Ecuador's President Rafael Correa announced today that creating a common citizenship is a goal in which "South America, in this case, really, must learn from Europe."
Correa, who attended the sixth presidential summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) in Lima, told state broadcaster TV Perú that Europeans "killed themselves in World War 2" and in other conflicts, "but now they are practically one homeland."
In this sense, he defended the project to create South American citizenship, which is supported by Unasur member countries.
"There is a need for the free movement of citizens and workers within any South American country, which is already taking place between the members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary areas that want to take us back to the past," he said.
The Ecuadorian president has said, among other things, that he agrees with the regrouping of the Organization of American States (OAS) on the condition that the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states is reduced and those who signed the San Jose Pact on Human Rights are taken into account.
"Those in the lead never commit to anything, and we South Americans, on the contrary, sign everything.
It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights in Washington is funded by the United States," he said, referring to political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
President Correa confirmed that he did not regret the decision, as it did not betray his principles and respected his "deep democratic values and human rights."
He added that at the time, "there were reasonable grounds to suspect that Assange might be extradited to a third country regardless of the ongoing trial."
In addition, he criticised the Swedish judiciary for asking him to submit to questioning on Swedish territory for an alleged sexual offence, while "Sweden's own legislation allows for questioning by video conference call, which could take place from the Ecuadorian embassy in London."
Correa said there was a risk that Assange's physical and mental health would deteriorate.
"I haven't spoken to him since he's been in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he has minor lung problems, but nothing serious," the Ecuadorian head of state said.
"However, there is a risk that his physical and mental condition will deteriorate because he is confined in a small space without the possibility of movement in the fresh air.
That would affect everyone's health," he added.
President Correa noted that the solution of the asylum granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian embassy in London under a permit allowing him to travel to Ecuador is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and European courts, stressing that talks had taken place with London to resolve the imprisonment of the WikiLeaks founder.
"We do not negotiate on human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there were constant talks.
The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European courts, because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, is conducting a series of proceedings before various European instances," he said.
He said that "if the UK issues a pass tomorrow, everything will be over".
And if Sweden listens to Mr. Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as the legislation there allows without any problem and as has already been done in other cases, the problem will be put to an end tomorrow."
Correa took advantage of the situation to present himself as a defender of press freedom, making it clear that he certainly does not tolerate "mediocrity, bad intentions and lies that undermine freedom of expression."
The greatest enemies of a free press are not us, mean and perverse politicians, but bad journalists in the service of profit, coercion and blackmail," he said.
From this point of view, he expressed joy that neither such journalists, nor "the bankers, nor the hegemonic countries, nor the bourgeoisie dominate Ecuador," and said that if re-elected, "he will continue to make changes in the right direction and direction."
President Correa also backed the decision to maintain Paraguay's veto on Unasur membership at least until its next election, arguing that the whole "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and coupism cloaked in legality" because it has in fact "destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy."
In addition, the Ecuadorian president said that he considered "entirely appropriate" the desire of his Colombian counterpart Juan Manuel Santos to negotiate with Nicaragua on the maritime borders between the two countries now, in the aftermath of the ruling of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which ruled in favor of Nicaragua.
The verdict is currently not accepted.
"This is a problem between a South American and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to walk together.
They need to be considered broadly so that they can be overcome and be able to move forward."
He also expressed hope for a settlement of the maritime border dispute before Peru and Chile in the same court, expressing the view that "it is right for Latin America to seek international instances if both countries commit to accept a judgment, however harsh it may be."
Referring to the possibility of running in the next presidential election in Ecuador to run for a third term, he noted that he sees the possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes very difficult."
Correa said he would retire from public life if he lost the February 2013 election.
"Personally, I have never been interested in power, but such unjust situations as socio-economic poverty in Ecuador can only be remedied by political power.
My political movement believed that it was me who guaranteed this likely victory, so we must accept this responsibility," he said.
"If I win, it would be my last term as president and then I would retire from politics.
If we lose, the same thing awaits me.
I have already decided," he said.
Correa also mentioned Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez's new medical treatment in Cuba.
"I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro, who says that President Chavez has left for a planned routine treatment and his return to Cuba was expected after the end of the campaign.
This is not a relapse in the health of the president," he explained.
The head of state of Ecuador today attended the sixth summit of heads of state and government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which concluded with calls for greater regional integration to sustain development, equality and security.
AIDS victims today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when the result of his test was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was as if I had been struck by lightning," he says, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor tried to "soften a little" but apparently to no avail.
The boy kept it a secret from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own shoulders and began to inform himself about it. And with such enthusiasm that he has already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the earliest patients of the HIV Unit at the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), which he came to in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something unimaginable in the early 90s when there were a lot of doubt, few treatment options and a greater stigma.
At that time, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him "because he had a cut."
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are many people who do not know about their disease and come only when the virus has caused destruction of the body and exhausted the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since the appearance of AIDS in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, "it means a great achievement that the life expectancy of a patient who starts treatment early and appropriately is exactly the same as in healthy people", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Guadalajara Civil Hospital, adding that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Andrade Villanueva, an infectologist and HIV/AIDS specialist, explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008, AIDS is not a death sentence, but that survival and full life depends on the degree of disability of the immune system of patients who are diagnosed with the disease, with those who do not use drugs better off: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years, and people with 500 CD4 cells can live up to 50 years.
Put simply, this means that someone diagnosed with HIV at age 25 can "live smoothly until the age of 75 if they follow treatment," the doctor explained in an interview.
To underline this progress, it is worth remembering that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died from AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (United Nations Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS Yearbook), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 so far as May this year. However, universal access to antiretroviral medicines has been ensured since 2005.
- Why do people continue to die from the disease?
- "It seems to me that the problem is not in the possibilities of access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it happens in our hospital.
For at least the last 12 years, we have not exhausted our stocks of medicines. The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage because they don't know the state of infection, that is, at a late stage of the disease."
He adds a convincing figure: "Nine out of ten patients come when an associated infection occurs. The only thing that needs to be done to have a greater influence on overall mortality is to diagnose the disease earlier, and therefore we need to offer disease detection tests on a large scale to all those who request them."
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the State Council for AIDS Prevention in the state of Jalisco, as well as with patients like Fabrizio, who came to have tests done in a private laboratory just because a friend did it, and despite his young age, he had already developed AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma.  cancer, which is one of the usual complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die and don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather go on a rampage three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
The change was for the better, I eat healthily, exercise, take medication."
To this day, all his parents know is that he suffered from cancer.
"I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I take care of myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who has accepted the invitation to share his experience with MILENIO JALISCO to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today, on World AIDS Day.
"Let them get tested. If they took a risk, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV positive, it's better. And if they've been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like everyone else if they're responsible."
This message sums up the slogan of the battle against AIDS this year 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who researches HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "there has really been an increase in the distribution of condoms, they used to give us one or two, now they give us packets of hundreds of condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms," he said.
Among the most susceptible to new infections are adolescents.
"What do you want it for?" is a common question full of irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy employees and medical staff that teens want to avoid, says the reporter.
He proposed to change this inefficient distribution. Let the condoms not only be behind the counters, but the hundred should be in dispensers in public toilets, in places where young people often go.
"It's not promoting promiscuity.
Nor is it about "paying them beer and a motel," as Gov. Emilio González responded when asked if he would agree to distribute condoms in his district.
There is no such sexuality. It's best to make condoms available to those who already have sex lives," he said.
Key figures in Jalisco
There were 13,435 cases (12,158 AIDS cases and 1,317 HIV cases).
This ranks fourth in new and identified AIDS cases and 13th in HIV-related cases in Mexico.
92% of infections occur sexually, 6% through the blood route and 2% perinatally.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are four to five people per registered case who do not know about the disease.
The judgment approved by the United States Court of Appeal, which does not recognise Grupo Vitro's debt restructuring provided for by the bankruptcy in Mexico, sets an ominous precedent for any national enterprise with branches in a neighbouring country and solvency problems.
Thus, the corporate restructuring procedures allowed by Mexican law do not seem to apply in the land of stripes and stars, despite international agreements.
The approval of a ruling handed down on June 15 last year by Judge Harlin Hal at the North Texas Bankruptcy Court leaves Mexican companies without defense against the possibility of confiscation of their assets on the other side of the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door for Mexico's main glass maker to appeal three irregularities.
At the outset, while the judge in this case argues that creditors should abide by U.S. bankruptcy law, the Fifth District Court of Appeals based in New Orleans says that the main procedure provides for bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
Firstly, it would show ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
In essence, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created for this purpose, designating the American Law Institute as the arbiter.
Secondly, the judgment provides that without a vote by the branches from the internal corporate structure, recognising the indebtedness of the parent company Vitro to the subsidiaries, the required majority for approval of the restructuring would not have been reached.
However, Mexican law allows for this possibility.
The fact is that the case of Vitro was not the first in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, such as Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose internal debts were guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Institute.
Moreover, it is true that, even after deducting the votes of the branches, the creditors - who were against Vitro in court in the United States, i.e. 'vulture funds' such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not have reached a majority.
They would get about 45 percent to 37 percent in the vote.
This information is disregarded by the Court of Appeal.
From another point of view, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the backdrop of the serious economic crisis that has hit the United States.
In the meantime, González Sada's family business will file an appeal for reconsideration directly with the Court of Appeal, so that the review will take place with full participation, that is, with the participation of five judges, since only three originally voted.
If he does not succeed here, he will seek as a remedy a review of the process by a higher instance, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
What is significant about the case is that the court omitted a document sent by the Mexican government as an amicus curiae department detailing Vitro's conduct under the Bankruptcy Act and pointing out that the company had made a concession by adhering to agreements signed by both countries in order to confront the law with Chapter 15 of the United States Insolvency Act.
Moreover, it is pointed out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. rules for international insolvency cases that guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
Impact on both sides: punishment for both Vitro and the state.
Overall rating
