A course that explores the "end of the world" begins
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to take a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew it was an irresistible attraction: The end of the "long count" Mayan calendar, due on December 21, was seized upon by many as proof that the end of the world was coming.
But Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the next few months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the budget gap some call "debt Armageddon," and the growing conflict in which Israel is embroiled, the place where Christians theorizing about the end of the world say the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
When one discusses what is happening in the world today as if we have 30 days left, it is a really good time.
And remember that bad means good to apocalyptic-minded people.
And he's not the only professor offering courses on "the end of the world" in this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, assistant professor Barry Vacker runs a course on "The Means, Culture, and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
"We discuss why these ideas expand over time," he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that govern certain human behaviors.
For example, if nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, war can break out.
This month, students are analyzing movies with apocalyptic themes and exploring how they differ from real-life examples.
"I tried to inform students about what was possible, likely, believable and impossible," Vacker says.
On Pennsylvania State University's main campus, Latin history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, teamed up to run a course simply titled The End of the World.
"We don't add '2012' because we always count on the possibility of holding the course again in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "impending destruction", students have to study, create projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will take place on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
Courses have become quite popular.
"It stretched out to two hours," Restall said of his course for 35 high-average students.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we received e-mail inquiries asking if there was still space.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves," said Bridgid Robinson, 23, a religion and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers University in Camden.
Thus, apocalyptic, secular, or religious thinking is only a matter of consolation or the absence thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he's seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of a class where it could be taught before," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But no student interviewed, let alone a professor, said they believed in an end date of December 21.
"Our first project was about the Mayan prediction and we're refuting it in a way," said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old final year student at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point on the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, by which people respond to changes in their surroundings by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused this speculation to flourish.
"Elsewhere, people don't think about it," he said.
This happens overwhelmingly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is lecturing in the Philippines this year, was quick to answer when asked if he knew of a course on "the end of the world."
"The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world," he wrote, hinting at an exception to the highest office.
We have grace from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many days of the final judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will cease to exist.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors alike.
Several said they intended to go to the "end of the world" festivities.
"I'll probably call some friends to laugh together," said Samira Ford, a twenty-year-old communications student.
